<BYLINE>John McCallum</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCallum </PERSON>, a former syndicated sports columnist and author of 35 books, died Saturday of cardiac arrest at age 64. <PERSON> McCallum </PERSON> wrote for <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> newspapers for a number of years and then moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He wrote a sports column for the <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a national news service. <PERSON> McCallum </PERSON> was best known for works on sports figures, including `` The Tiger Wore Spikes,'' about baseball great <PERSON> Ty </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON>, and `` Dumb <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>,'' about a boxer in the <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> era. He also wrote books on figures such as the late <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>, actress <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> and former <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON>.
