<FIRST>u i PM-Argentina-Electricity     12-20 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina-Electricity,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moon Over Buenos Aires _ For Lack Of Artificial Light</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At night, the brightest light shining in this <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> city of 10 million is cast by the moon. Spotlights on public monuments, the flashing neon glare of billboards, lights in office towers, store windows and even on a Christmas tree near a main thoroughfare have been turned down or even off by government order. There is an electricity shortage. Streetlights have been dimmed by 50 percent. Drivers, who usually careen along narrow, often cobblestone streets downtown with only their cars' parking lights have taken to turning on low beams. The problem stems from seasonally low levels of water in the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Limay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Neuquen </LOCATION> rivers that feed hydroelectric stations and the shutdown for repairs or maintenance of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s two nuclear power plants. The system `` is working at the limit of its capacity, and we should be prepared for whatever eventuality and are running the risk of a total outage,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Larriqueta </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. Portenos, as residents of this port city are called, have had to make do with rotating, scheduled outages of five hours a day since last week. City residents have become accustomed to summertime electricity shortages as the city has grown faster than its public services can handle. Blackouts, which have occurred half a dozen times since 1965, are relatively rare, however. The last occurred in November 1985. The latest scheduled outages have meant walking up flights of stairs for lack of working elevators, sweating in late spring heat for lack of air conditioning, and dodging four, five and sometimes six lanes of cars at rush hour for lack of functioning traffic signals. Beginning today, the hours of the three government-controlled television stations in this capital city will be cut back to 12 hours _ noon to midnight. The two private stations have been requested by the government to do likewise. The usual hours of operation are 7 a.m. to 3 a.m. Nighttime events like horseracing at the <LOCATION> Hipodromo </LOCATION> and concerts have been canceled until further notice unless the facility has its own source of electricity. Soccer games, usually played at night to avoid daytime heat, have been rescheduled for the afternoon. At the huge Salto Grande hydroelectric complex on the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> north of the capital, only one of 14 turbines was operating Tuesday. The rest were idled by lack of water. The Atucha nuclear power plant, about 60 miles north of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, has been shut down since August for repairs to its cooling system. The Embalse station, 465 miles to the west of the capital, is undergoing routine maintenance. About three weeks ago, the government for the first time in years ordered clocks to be set back one hour to take advantage of the extra daylight. The time change will stay in effect at least until Jan. 15, when one of the nuclear plants should be back on line, said <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, director of planning at the the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>' energy secretariat Water levels probably wo n't rise until seasonal rains return in May, he said. On the lighter side, energy restrictions will be lifted the following two weekends for Christmas and New Year's, a government spokesman said.
