<HEAD>Energy Department Expects Agreement on Ohio Plant Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A consent decree may be reached by the end of the week for the cleanup of a federally owned uranium enrichment plant in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official says. An agreement to clean up the <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION> Gaseous Diffusion Plant near <LOCATION> Piketon </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> was announced last month by <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> and state Attorney General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Celebrezze </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. However, the plan still was under review by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, spokesman <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Elmets </PERSON> said. A senior department official, who asked that he not be identified, said the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> `` may have a decision by the end of the week on a consent decree'' that would involve court supervision of a cleanup. When <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> and <PERSON> Celebrezze </PERSON> announced the $ 50 million cleanup plan last month, they said it was significant because the federal agency would be bound by state law and regulation. The <LOCATION> Piketon </LOCATION> plant processes uranium for fuel for commercial nuclear power reactors. It generates toxic wastes such as polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, solvents and metals, as well as radioactive materials. When the agreement was announced Nov. 22, <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> said he hoped it would serve as a model for other tough cleanup cases, such as the government-owned Fernald plant near <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. Environmental officials say that plant has dumped radioactive waste improperly, possibly contaminating ground water, since it began processing uranium for nuclear weapons in 1951. The <LOCATION> Piketon </LOCATION> plan calls for the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to be subject to orders issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, which would supervise the cleanup of about 6 million pounds of waste. Last month, officials said the agreement still needed to be incorporated into a federal court consent decree.
