<FIRST>r w PM-FAA-HighDensity     12-20 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FAA-High Density,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Proposes Change in Airport `High Density' Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Large airlines at four major airports would have to prove they make heavy use of their takeoff and landing slots or risk losing them to other carriers, under a proposed federal rule change. The proposal, released Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, would revise the `` high density'' rule at <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> O'Hare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> National. The rule, adopted in 1969, limits the number of takeoff and landing slots at the airports during heavy traffic periods. Currently, airlines must show that they are using those slots during 65 percent of the heavy traffic hours over a two-month period. The new proposal would require large air carriers with 10 or more slots to show that the slots are being used at a 90 percent rate or the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> would consider withdrawing them. The requirement would be 80 percent for carriers with five to nine slots and would stay at 65 percent for all others. The slots that are taken away from an airline could then be available for sale or reallocation to a different airline, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. The change would `` increase opportunity for new entrant carriers to have access to high-density airports, and for small incumbent carriers to increase the number of operations at those airports,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> said his company was `` encouraged'' that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> wanted to make sure the takeoff and landing slots are fully utilized. `` We're using every single slot we have,'' <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> said. `` At some airports we obviously could use more.'' He said that in some cases, airlines have held their slots without fully using them. The limits on takeoff and landing slots are necessary because an airport's air traffic control system has limited capacity, <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> said. `` We are not in favor of any slot program at all if it can be avoided,'' <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> said, but eliminating the system would require costly expansion of the air traffic control systems. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> is seeking public and aircraft industry comments on its proposal.
</TEXT>
