<HEAD>Homeless Man Reluctantly Accepts Inheritance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> is homeless, wealthy and unwilling to change even though his health may someday force him to use the $ 190,000 estate he inherited from his parents in 1979. The 71-year-old recently agreed to claim the inheritance, which has grown to $ 207,421, but said he has no intention of changing his lifestyle. For the last 20 years, <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> has lived in alleys or boarding rooms. He likes his lifestyle and has no use for money, the former cab driver said during a street corner interview last week. `` I do n't want it. When you're young, the money means something,'' he said, refusing a lengthy interview or photographs. If he did have money, he said, he would just lose it to thieves. <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> said he has known about the money since his father died in 1979. He claimed it only because of pressure from relatives, he said. <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>'s father, a blacksmith named <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>, left the estate to his son, said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Landon </PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION> Controller </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. When the inheritance went unclaimed, the account was turned over to the county <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrator </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, then to the state, said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Zingale </PERSON>, a special assistant to the state controller in the Division of Unclaimed Property. <PERSON> Zingale </PERSON> said <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>'s cousin, <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> <PERSON> Weitzman </PERSON>, contacted him in September 1987 asking for help in her efforts to get <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> to claim the money. <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> was uninterested, but more than a year later, he did sign documents, <PERSON> Zin