<HEAD>Inmates Do Their Holiday Shopping By Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mail-order catalog firm that has begun catering to the captive audience of prisoners reports Christmas sales are on the rise. `` They are very good customers and it's developed into a substantial segment of our business. Where else are they going to go?'' said <PERSON> Mortimer </PERSON> <PERSON> Polep </PERSON>, chairman of the Holyoke-based <ORGANIZATION> Paysaver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catalog </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Showrooms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We even got a thank-you letter from one inmate who said, ` After all, our money is as good as the guy that has n't been caught yet,''' he said. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> of the 2,000-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Order </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said it's impossible to tell how many inmates order from catalogs, but sales seem to be up everywhere. `` We do n't keep any special statistics on sales to prison inmates, but my sense is that they have been increasing as prisons have eased the regulations on what kinds of packages prisoners can receive,'' he said. <PERSON> Polep </PERSON> said his company's Christmas sales to prisoners are up 25 percent this year, but he wo n't divulge exactly how big his business is behind bars. At the 1,100-inmate state prison at <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, Sgt. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> said he inspects about 30 packages a day that inmates have ordered from catalogs. `` We do n't allow them anything like hacksaws or shotguns,'' he said. For the three weeks before Christmas, however, the prison suspends its rules against mailed food and allows inmates to receive packages up to 25 pounds holding mail-order and homemade delicacies. To inspect the food packages, the prison must hold up inspections of other packages, which wait until after Christmas to reach inmates. `` The food is more important and meaningful to them anyway,'' <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> said. `` They can get clothes all year.'' The largest purveyors to the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> prisoners are <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>, an Illinois-based catalog firm specializing in low-cost items, followed by Service Merchandise of <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and merchandising giants <ORGANIZATION> J.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> said. Clothing is the big sales item at the medium-security prison, followed by towels, television sets, radios and fans, he said. `` We've put together a little booklet on what they can order, but essentially it's any basic necessity,'' <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> said. `` They know by word of mouth that if there were any problems with anyone trying to bring in weapons or drugs, we would cut back on the orders and we can trace it right back to who is responsible.'' Payments are made by the prison against inmate accounts, he said. They build up accounts by working in prison, or by getting money from their families. Regulations on what prisoners can order vary widely from state to state and prison to prison, according to state and federal officials, with federal prisoners allowed only limited catalog-ordering privileges. `` They have to have special prior permission, but half the time the issue is not so much the regulations but the fact that our inmates just do n't have the money,'' said <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the federal bureau of prisons. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> treats its prison customers `` just like any others,'' said spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gucfa </PERSON>, except that it delivers packages directly to the prisons rather than to its retail stores. `` Obviously they ca n't get out to pick up their packages,'' she said. But <PERSON> Paysaver </PERSON> has employees assigned just to its prison business, and Christmas is a particularly busy time. The woman in charge of the company's prison sales, who asked that her name not be used, said some of her dealings with inmates `` have helped restore my faith in human nature. `` Sometimes they do n't figure the shipping charges right and if it's just a couple of dollars, I send it out and just tuck a note inside as to what is owed and almost always I get a check back,'' she said. `` I got a letter from a man at <LOCATION> Attica </LOCATION> -LRB- in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> -RRB- who said he was sending Christmas presents to his kids in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and asked if I could put a note inside the package saying, ` With love, from Daddy.'''
