<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar closed higher against the Japanese yen Tuesday, while share prices rebounded on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 124.70 yen, up 0.68 yen from Monday's close of 124.02 yen. After opening at 124.45 yen, the currency moved in a range of 124.30 to 124.80 yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost 66.63 points on Monday, climbed 97.86 points, or 0.3 percent, finishing at 29,567.94. On Monday, the index closed at 29,470.08. Individual investors showed interest in steels, while institutional investors remained on the sidelines amid speculation over a possible <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> discount rate hike, said <PERSON> Yoshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimoyama </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. In foreign exchange trading, dealers attributed the dollar's higher opening in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to the currency's early strength on the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> market, which opened earlier Market players in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> bought the currency in expectation of a discount rate increase in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The discount rate is the interest the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> central bank, charges on loans to commercial banks. Many market watchers have been anticipating a discount rate hike in recent weeks as part of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s attempts to prevent resurgent inflation. Higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates increase the returns on dollar-denominated investments.
