<HEAD>Relatives of Victims Curse Government On Anniversary Of Ferry
Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of people wailed and called down a curse on the government and a shipping line today in emotional ceremonies marking the first anniversary of history's worst peacetime disaster at sea The 300 protesters were marking the Dec. 20, 1987, sinking of the ferry <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> and the oil tanker Vector, which collided and exploded off <LOCATION> Mindoro </LOCATION> island, leaving more than 3,000 people dead. `` In the name of all our loved ones, wherever they are, we swear that all those responsible shall be made to pay for the deaths and injustices they caused,'' the crowd chanted in unison. `` We will not lose hope until all those responsible are punished.'' A presidential commission said at least 3,563 people were aboard the two ships, but only 26 survived. Survivors and relatives claim the government and the <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON>'s owners, <ORGANIZATION> Sulpicio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, have not provided adequate compensation nor taken steps to prevent other maritime disasters. The protesters, including at least four survivors and relatives of <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> victims, assembled at a <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s church for a Mass, then marched toward President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s office at Malacanang Palace. About 20 police officers and vehicles blocked the marchers at a bridge about 600 feet from the palace but permitted the marchers to hold a rally. After speeches, the protesters lit candles and set fire to papier-mache models of the two ships. Two men slit the throats of two chickens and spattered the models with the blood. As the flames triggered firecrackers inside the models, hundreds wailed and began reciting the curse, traditional among people of the central <LOCATION> Visayas </LOCATION> islands from where most of the victims came. During the rally, survivor <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> <PERSON> Galang </PERSON> told the crowd that the <ORGANIZATION> Sulpicio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> had offered him money to testify that the oil tanker was at fault but he refused. `` They think they can buy lives with their money,'' he said. He said the survivors were being victimized by owners `` and this uncaring government.'' Speaker <PERSON> Ildefonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Aresala </PERSON>, who said he lost his entire family in the disaster, said his claims for compensation had been bogged down by paperwork. `` I thought the president would be able to help, but I was mistaken,'' he said. `` There's no clear solution. This is very painful for us. I do n't know what kind of law we have.'' Other relatives of victims claimed the government was simply pressuring them into accepting inadequate compensation offered by the ship owners. `` For as long as the government adopts a system that favors the interests of greedy capitalists, corruption will continue endlessly and sea travelers will never be safe,'' said one leaflet distributed in the crowd. <PERSON> Nazzer </PERSON> <PERSON> Cajolo </PERSON>, who claimed he lost five brothers in the disaster, said Sulpicio offered a $ 7,500 settlement but his family rejected it. `` Now they say my brothers are alive,'' he added. `` We want this government to listen to us and not avoid us.'' Cajolo is one of about 300 people who have filed a class suit against <ORGANIZATION> Sulpicio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, the largest Philippine domestic shipping company. The suit was rejected by a lower court but an appeal is pending. In October, another Sulpicio passenger ship, the <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, sank during Typhoon Ruby with about 500 people aboard. About half those aboard died or are missing.
