<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained against the Japanese yen today, while share prices rebounded moderately on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 124.70 yen, up 0.68 yen from Monday's close of 124.02 yen. After opening at 124.45 yen, the currency moved in a range of 124.30 to 124.80 yen. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's higher opening in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> followed its rise on the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> market, which opened earlier, dealers said. <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Mitsuhiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinugasa </PERSON> said the dollar-yen rate hardly moved in the morning session, but increased dollar-buying by speculative investors and trading companies in the afternoon pushed the dollar up. `` There was no economic factor in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> that raised the dollar today, but its firmness on overseas markets encouraged investors' buying,'' <PERSON> Kinugasa </PERSON> added On the stock market, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 66.63-point loser Monday, climbed 97.86 points, or 0.3 percent, closing at 29,567.94. Dealers attributed the index's quick rise in the morning to an overnight gain in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The Nikkei gained 151 points in the morning session, but eased somewhat in the afternoon as buying interest fell, dealers said. Most institutional investors were sitting on the sidelines in the afternoon due to uncertainties over the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> discount rate, said a dealer at one major securities firm, speaking on condition of anonymity. Trading was thin with volume on the first section estimated at 650 million shares.
