<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today announced an amnesty for more than 2,000 `` politically motivated offenders,'' including two who were serving 20-year sentences for burning a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government building. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the clemency was approved at a special Cabinet session. Ministry officials said 281 prisoners would be released Wednesday, including <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyun-jang </PERSON> and <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> <PERSON> Boo-shik </PERSON>, who were serving 20-year sentences for leading a raid on the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Cultural Center in the southern city of <LOCATION> Pusan </LOCATION> in early 1982. Protesters set fire to the building to protest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the government of then-President <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON>. One person was killed and three were wounded. Another 1,581 people already freed on parole will have their civil rights restored Wednesday, 92 prisoners will have their sentences reduced, and 61 people who were sought by police will be taken off the wanted list, authorities said. Among those who will be granted restoration of civil rights is prominent dissident <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kun-tae </PERSON>, who was freed from prison in June, He received the <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Award </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> in April. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> was sentenced to five years in prison in 1986 for inciting unrest, but supporters alleged he was forced to confess by police torture. Prime Minister <PERSON> Kang </PERSON> <PERSON> Young-hoon </PERSON> said in a statement that the leniency was a `` bold step intended to heal the depressing wounds of the past era and thus to promote democratization.'' He said the action was taken through consultations with all major political parties, as had been promised by President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> pledged on Nov. 26 to release many political prisoners and institute other reforms to dissociate himself from <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, his predecessor. The main opposition <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> said the government amnesty was an important step toward democratization, but party officials said there were still 60 more political prisoners to be freed. The <ORGANIZATION> Reunification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, another opposition group, welcomed the measure, but dissident groups charged that <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> betrayed his promise for a total release of political prisoners by excluding about 300 political prisoners, mostly involved in movements for workers and depressed people. Government officials disagreed and claimed the figure was about 200 who were involved mostly in communist spy cases and other anti-state activities.
