<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There are two Quacks now but no <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>. The mystery of the purloined duckling deepened on Monday when a bronze duck stolen from a children's sculpture in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Public </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> more than a year ago was left at the <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> for police to find. But it was the wrong duck. To restore the sculpture, thieves must return a different duckling that was swiped on Dec. 10th. `` We're delighted to have Quack back but <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> is still missing,'' said the sculptor, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schon </PERSON> of suburban <LOCATION> Newton </LOCATION>. She pleaded with the culprit to return <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> the duck before Christmas. <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> and Quack are two of eight bronze ducklings shown waddling after their mother in a sculpture dramatizing <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McCloskey </PERSON>'s well-known children's story, `` Make Way for Ducklings. In the story, a family of ducks wanders around the <LOCATION> Beacon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> neighborhood before a friendly policeman helps them find a home in the Public Garden. Quack, the eighth duckling in the line, was stolen from the Garden while the cement was still setting on the sculpture in September 1987, <PERSON> Schon </PERSON> said. She replaced it and the ducklings remained untouched for more than a year. But this Dec. 10, while walking in the Garden, <PERSON> Schon </PERSON> noticed that <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, the fourth duck in the line, had disappeared. It had been cut off at the feet, apparenty with a blow torch, leaving only a telltale trace of bronze on the cobblestone. The ducklings each weigh about 30 pounds and are worth about $ 3,000. On Monday morning, <PERSON> Schon </PERSON> got a call from a friend saying the duckling had been found. A caller led police to the duck, which was in a cardboard box. `` I was joyous,'' she sai