<HEAD>Official Says Ruble Exchange Rate Won't Go Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The top trade official in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> government today denied the ruble will be devalued by 50 percent in 1990, as had been widely assumed in the West from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> media reports in the past two weeks. The newspaper articles, starting with one in <LOCATION> Sovietskaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Industria </LOCATION>, or Soviet Industry, had said the ruble exchange rate would fall by 50 percent `` on trade deals'' starting Jan. 1, 1990. Western economists and businessmen assumed this meant a drop from the current government-decreed exchange rate of $ 1.60 per ruble to 80 cents per ruble. But that applies only to the ruble's value in domestic deals among Soviet enterprises, not to its value in trade with foreigners, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamentsev </PERSON>, Deputy Chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION> and head of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, told a press briefing. `` This should not be taken as a change in the ruble standard versus foreign currency,'' <PERSON> Kamentsev </PERSON> said. He said the 50 percent change applies only to exchanges of foreign currency between various Soviet businesses, government-owned and cooperative. A Western diplomat, who declined to be named, noted at the time of the original report that it did not say which exchange rate would drop, a critical distinction as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reputedly has 3,000 different exchange rates for different products and different trading partners. <PERSON> Kamentsev </PERSON> refused to clarify that question. <PERSON> Kamentsev </PERSON> said, however, that the current change is one step in the direction of a ruble that someday will be freely convertible to foreign currency. He declined to name a date for convertibility, but said it would come after a major price reform. Rubles now are virtually worthless outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The Soviet government sells rubles to tourists and businessmen at a rate of $ 1.60 per ruble, but the black market rate is 25 to 30 cents per ruble. <PERSON> Kamentsev </PERSON> also said that starting next year, Soviet enterprises will be allowed to trade their foreign currency with other Soviet businesses in a thrice-yearly currency auction. However, he did not explain how the apparently open prices of an auction would co-exist with a set rate.
