ment installed. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> officials said <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> faced a stormy reception from his party's central committee. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> has already come under criticism from party hardliners such as <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>, a former defense minister, who expressed concern that <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s conciliatory stance would bring about an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> withdrawal from the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, where Palestinians have been in revolt for a year. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> today that because <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> favors a partial withdrawal from the occupied territories, a government with <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> was `` liable to bring about establishment of a PLO-Palestinian state and a continued Arab onslaught on the rest of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' He blamed `` daily attacks on Jews'' and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> for the political deadlock between the two parties, which have governed jointly since 1984. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> attacked <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s decision to join forces with <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> on Monday night by saying he thought <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> should be defense minister instead of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, Israeli news media reported. He reportedly accused <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> of failing to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> to `` take responsibility and rule.'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> reportedly replied by saying, `` if the defense portfolio were in <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>'s hands, we would have serious problems in the army.'' At least 332 Palestinians and 13 Israelis have been killed in the Arab revolt against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 21-year occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>.
