<HEAD>Prime Minister Wins Presidential Race; Violence Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th pvs, ``Premadasa said ...'' to UPDATE
with opposition reax. PICKS up 6th pvs, ``As promised ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>, vowing to halt ethnic violence on this <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> island, was elected president with slightly more than half the votes, the government said today. Earlier today, Sinhalese extremists hacked and shot to death nine supporters of <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s governing <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in a town east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, police said. `` The politics of terror has no place in the temple of democracy,'' <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> said in a televised address immediately after the announcement. `` I will eradicate fear and suppresion. I will restore law and order.'' <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> received 50.4 percent of the vote in Monday's election, edging former Prime Minister <PERSON> Sirimavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> of the opposition <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, according to Commissioner of Elections <PERSON> Chandrananda </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> has vowed to remove controversial Indian peacekeeping troops when he takes over <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s most powerful government post Jan. 2 for a six-year term. Ms. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> had no immediate comment on the balloting, and a man who answered the phone at her home said she was ill. But one of her close allies said she had described the results as `` unjust'' and would not accept them. The associate spoke on condition of anonymity and would not elaborate. As promised, outgoing President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> today dissolved <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and called new legislative elections for Feb. 15. He ordered an islandwide curfew to take effect after the official election results were announced. `` I particularly wish to ask, to appeal, to those who belong to the winning side, to treat your opponents who have lost with friendship, affection and love,'' he said. With all 182 polling districts counted, <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> had 2,569,199 votes, or 50.4 percent, compared with 2,299,770, or 45 percent for Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>, the election commissioner said. The remaining votes went to a leftist coalition candidate, <PERSON> Ossie </PERSON> <PERSON> Abeygoonesekera </PERSON>. The turnout was 55 percent, well below the nationwide rate of 80 percent in the 1982 presidential election as a campaign of imitidation by extremists apparently kept many people at home. Officials have blamed Sinhalese extremists of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> for the recent campaign of terror The extremists had threatened to kill anyone who voted on Monday. The military reported five Indian troops were killed in an ambush by Tamil ethnic minority rebels Monday, bringing the reported election day death toll to at least 20. Today's attacks occurred in <LOCATION> Bandarawela </LOCATION>, about 75 miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, local authorities said, speaking on condition of anonymity. They did not elaborate. The threats kept thousands from the polls. In the north, where militants of the Tamil minority are fighting for an independent state, many voting districts reported less than 10 percent turnout. And in the south, where Sinhalese extremists oppose government concessions to the Tamils, turnout ranged from 20 percent to 70 percent. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> was the standard-bearer for the party of <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>, who was barred by the constitution from seeking a third term. Under <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>'s rule, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> neared the brink of ruin because of ethnic violence that has killed nearly 10,000 people since 1983, when Tamils began an uprising against the Sinhalese. With the help of neighboring <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> _ the subcontinent's superpower and home to 60 million Tamils _ <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> signed a peace accord in July 1987 aimed at ending the Tamil insurgency The pact guaranteed some autonomy to the Tamils, who make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people _ and invited <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to help end the uprising by sending troops, which now number about 47,000. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> vehemently opposed the pact and vowed to kill anyone who supported the government after it was signed. The front has been blamed for hundreds of slayings since. Both <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>, who was prime minister in 1960-66 and 1970-77, opposed the Tamil accord. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> has called for the phased or immediate withdrawal of Indian troops. But Indian High Commissioner J.N. <PERSON> Dixit </PERSON> has indicated his country will not accept unilateral action. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> also campaigned as a champion of the poor and has promised a monthly $ 75 to the country's most impoverished families. He did not explain where the money would come from.
