<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Press freedom came under attack in 1988 from some of its staunchest defenders _ democratic countries such as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported. The plight of the media remained bleak under repressive regimes, but the trend in democrcies was the year's most worrisome development, the institute said in its annual `` World Press Freedom Review.'' `` One of the saddest truths facing the media around the world today is the growing trend toward government interference in democratic countries,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Galliner </PERSON>, the institute's director, wrote in the report's introduction. `` The hopes and encouragement of nations which are on their way towards more freedom and who rely on an example from countries with a democratic system, an open society and freedom, must not be crushed by governments in the free world,'' he said. The 32-page report cited `` significant improvements'' in press freedom in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, and setbacks in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> and other nations where journalism continues to be a sometimes dangerous and often difficult profession. While the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s policy of glasnost has meant `` heartening strides'' toward a more open press, restrictions on the reporting of subjects such as ethnic violence in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> have been a `` disgrace,'' the report said. The institute, which has offices in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, is an independent body representing 2,000 publishers and editors in more than 60 countries. Its report this year detailed developments in 82 countries. In 1988, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration `` continued its efforts to limit public access to information held by the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> government,'' the report said. It cited as a `` blatant example'' of interference in the media the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s upholding of the conviction of a former intelligence analyst for giving satellite photographs of a Soviet ship to a British magazine. The analyst, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Loring </PERSON> <PERSON> Morison </PERSON>, was sentenced to two years in prison. The report also criticized the new Canada-U.S. Free Trade Agreement for restricting Canadian journalists who can work in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to those with a university degree and three years' experience `` Attempts to define qualifications for journalists ... pose a serious threat,'' it said, noting it was the first time the rule was `` enshrined in an international accord.'' In <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the press scored a victory when Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government lost its court fight to prevent newspapers from publishing extracts from `` Spycatcher,'' the memoirs of former intelligence agent <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. However, the report criticized <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s ban on all radio and television interviews with 11 groups in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, including the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and its political wing, <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>. The report called the ban `` the most drastic action taken against British broadcasters in peacetime.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> was forced at the last minute to withdraw legislation that would have shifted the duty of proving defamation from plaintiffs to journalists, the report said. An Australian court ordered a journalist to reveal his sources, and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s press had an `` appalling year,'' marked by three-month publication bans for two newspapers and a one-month ban on another, it said. Elsewhere, `` the media under dictatorships remained all too predictably under lock and key,'' the report noted. One of the worst years ever for the independent press in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> was marked by violent assaults on 24 foreign and Chilean journalists. Five journalists were forced to leave <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> following the passage of an anti-terrorist law. <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> cracked down on their press, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> continued to do so and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> soured a promising start by reasserting control and suppressing negative news, the report said. However, the South Korean press had a `` watershed year,'' with many visible and invisible restrictions lifted, and in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, economic and political liberalizations were extended to the media, the report said.
