<SECOND>PM-UN-Drug Conference,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Conference Adopts Convention Against Illicit Drug Trafficking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> conference today an adopted an international convention against illicit drug trafficking and drug abuse that it hopes will deal an efficient blow to those who sell and use drugs. `` It's significant because it represents a commitment by over a hundred other nations to cooperate in fighting the problems of drug trafficking and drug abuse,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` It's apparent that no one nation alone or within its own borders can deal with the multinational operations of the drug cartels,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. The convention for the first time gives all signatory countries the right of extradition of suspected drug traffickers and the right to confiscate all their assets. The document, first conceived four years ago, was signed by 43 countries, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, at the close of the monthlong <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> conference. Sixty-three other nations participating in the closed-door gathering adopted the convention by consensus, according to <PERSON> Axel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wuestenhage </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Information office. It may take several years for the new convention to become legally binding. To have legal force, it must be ratified by parliaments or other national bodies in the signatory countries, then given to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general for notification. Many conference delegates were optimistic. Asked how the new convention matched recent anti-drug legislation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said, `` It's a very good fit.' The provisions on money laundering, confiscation of drug dealers' assets and cooperation in pursuing the traffickers are similar to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> legislation signed last month, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would need only `` a minor adjustment'' to comply with Article 3 of the Convention, he added. That article deals with the identification, tracing, freezing and forfeiture of proceeds derived from drug trafficking. The article is seen as a major way to toughen two earlier international accords by cracking down on modern drug traffickers whose networks straddle the world and involve billions of dollars. The new document, known formally as the Convention Against Illicit Trafic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances, complements the 1961 Convention on <ORGANIZATION> Narcotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drugs </ORGANIZATION> signed by 121 contries and the 1971 Convention on Psychotropic Substances so far ratified by 88 countries. Besides providing for asset forfeiture and extradition, the new document foresees mutual legal assistance and cooperation in training police and customs officers fighting drugs. It also stipulates how to monitor substances frequently used in the illicit manufacture of drugs, to eradicate illicit plant cultivation and suppress traffic by sea, in free-trade zones and free ports. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would have preferred stronger language on extradition, with those engaged in crimes linked to drug trafficking eligible for extradition `` irrespective of their nationality whenever they may be found.'' A special international commission will be charged with monitoring implementation, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. Asked about the cooperation of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, with its strict laws on banking secrecy, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had experience with <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> which proved `` very positive ... with regard to waiving bank secrecy laws when criminal conduct is involved.''
