<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> leader pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor conspiracy charge stemming from a 1979 gunfight and brawl between Klansmen and black marchers. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, who was `` exalted cyclops'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Cullman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klavern </ORGANIZATION> in 1979, admitted conspiring with other Klansmen to disrupt the march in <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> by blacks, who were protesting the arrest of a black man in the rapes of three white women. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> entered his guilty plea Monday in federal court in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>. Prosecutors have not recommended a sentence; <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> delayed sentencing until at least late January. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> faces up to one year in prison and a $ 1,000 fine. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> is the third former Klansman to plead guilty in the case. A federal jury convicted a fourth man; five others are scheduled to stand trial Jan. 9 in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>. The clash came during one of several protests blacks staged after the arrest of <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON>, who was charged with raping the three white women in 1978. One march ended in a gunfight and brawl with Klansmen in downtown <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> in which several marchers and policemen were injured. <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> was convicted of one of the rape counts and sent to prison. The <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> later ruled that he was mentally incompetent, and he was moved to a mental hospital. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Spina </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, said the former Klansman pleaded guilty in part because <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> ruled last month that the conspiracy charge was a misdemeanor rather than a felony. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused last week to review several legal challenges to court rulings the Klan defendants had pursued, clearing the way for the January trial, <PERSON> Spina </PERSON> said.
