editing pvs to conform; Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Miss Myerson ...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal jury deliberating charges against former <ORGANIZATION> Miss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Bess </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> asked today to rehear some of the testimony from the prosecution's star witness. Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> and two others are charged with a divorce-fixing conspiracy. After 12 weeks of testimony, the jury began deliberating Monday and resumed today. In late morning the panel asked to re-hear testimony by <PERSON> Sukhreet </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> as well as the judge's instructions about direct and circumstantial evidence. Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>, who was Miss <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in 1945; her lover, one-time city contractor <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> `` <PERSON> Andy </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>, 43; and former state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Hortense </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON>, 76, are charged with plotting to cut <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>'s temporary support payments to his estranged wife. All three are charged with conspiracy, mail fraud and aiding the violation of state bribery laws. `` The gist of conspiracy is agreement,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> explained to jurors Monday during nearly three hours of instructions. It was n't necessary to find any illegal activity `` actually had been carried out'' for a conspiracy conviction, he said, adding that they simply `` must find there was a meeting of the minds of at least two of the defendants.'' Prosecutors contended that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>, 64, the city's former cultural affairs commissioner, bribed Mrs. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> by giving a $ 19,000-a-year city job to the judge's emotionally troubled and chronically unemployed daughter, <PERSON> Sukhreet </PERSON>, 39. Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> also faces an obstruction of justice count for an alleged attempt to influence the grand jury testimony of Ms. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON>. The key witness on that count was Ms. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON>, who conceded in her testimony that her version of the facts had changed in the past and might change again. She also said that electroshock treatment she underwent for clinical depression left her memory, at times, `` like Swiss cheese.'' None of the defendants testified in their own behalf and <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> told jurors it would be `` unfair, improper and indeed un-American'' to hold that against them. The prosecution's case consisted mainly of circumstantial evidence because there were no witnesses to the alleged bribe scheme. There were, however, two undisputed, facts: <PERSON> Sukhreet </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON> was hired as Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>'s personal assistant in late August 1983, and the judge slashed <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>'s interim support payments from $ 1,850 a week to $ 850 a week on Sept. 14, 1983. The defense contended that Ms. <PERSON> Gabel </PERSON>'s hiring may have been unwise but was not illegal. The defense also offered legal and financial explanations for the lowering of <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>'s support payments. Miss <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> faces a maximum of 30 years in prison and $ 513,000 in fines if convicted on all counts. Her two co-defendants face up to 25 years and $ 263,000 in fines. <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON>, once a multimillionaire city sewage contractor, is serving a three-year prison term for income tax evasion.
