<HEAD>Record Number of Japanese Traveled Abroad in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A record 6.83 million Japanese traveled abroad in 1987, taking advantage of the yen's continued strengthening against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, the government said Tuesday. The number was up 23.8 percent from the previous record of 5.52 million in 1986, according to an annual report. `` We believe we'll be able to see 10 million people -LRB- a year -RRB- going abroad within five years,'' said <PERSON> Yasushi </PERSON> <PERSON> Babasaki </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s Research and Planning Division. In 1987, the Japanese government launched a program to double the number of Japanese travelers abroad in a five-year period to help give this nation of 120 million a more international outlook. The number of foreign visitors to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> last year rose 4.5 percent to 2.16 million, but still was below the 1985 figure of 2.33 million visitors, the paper said. The yen's value against the dollar has nearly doubled since September 1985, making foreign visits cheaper for Japanese and visits to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> more expensive for foreigners.
