<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The washed-up medical waste and other debris that spoiled <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City-area </LOCATION> beaches last summer came from several sources, including a landfill, sewer overflows, garbage transfer stations and storm water outlets, state officials say. `` We have not found any evidence of a single culprit discharging the medical waste,'' Environmental Conservation Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jorling </PERSON> said as he released a report on an investigation into the waste. Several of the state's most popular beaches had to be closed temporarily during the area's hottest summer in decades when debris _ including syringes and blood vials _ came ashore. Waste washups also resulted in beach closings in other Eastern states, including <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, as well as along <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. The report blamed the washups primarily on inadequate garbage handling in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and on the weather. Medical waste accounted for only 1 percent to 10 percent of the washed up debris. <PERSON> Jorling </PERSON> said Monday the highly publicized beach closings pointed to the need for more stringent controls on all garbage, including medical waste. The report highlights the need for change in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s sewage and landfill systems, said a spokesman for a national environmental organization `` While an army of state, federal and local people have been looking for midnight dumpers, the real villain here may actually be the city sewer system and the city's landfills,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Izeman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN