<HEAD>AIDS On Track To Become Fifth-Leading Killer Among Youth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 7th, 8th, 10th grafs to correct numbers mentioned
with corresponding lists of major causes of death among various age
groups</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 AIDS in a few years is likely to become the fifth leading killer of Americans from birth to age 24 if present trends continue, say federal health officials. Meanwhile, a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report says President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Domestic Policy Council got in the way of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials' attempts at launching an anti-AIDS education program in the spring of 1987. The report is also critical of television networks for declining to run many anti-AIDS public service spots when they did become available, particularly those dealing with condoms as a way to prevent spread of the deadly virus. The report, issued last week, said further that ther were problems with getting a national AIDS hotline operating at full speed, although it said those lapses had been mostly corrected by last summer. Meanwhile, Dr. <PERSON> Antonia </PERSON> <PERSON> Novello </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> on Monday that AIDS is already the ninth leading cause of death among children 1 to 4 years old and the seventh leading cause of deaths among young people age 15 to 24. If present trends continue, she said, the disease soon will move up to No. 5. The five leading causes of death among people age 15 to 24 in 1985, the last year for which figures are available, were accidents, suicide, homicide, cancer and heart disease. For people age 5 to 14, the top five in 1985 were accidents, cancer, birth defects, homicide and heart disease. For children from 1 to 4, the top four were accidents, birth defects, cancer, and heart disease. For infants under 1, the leading causes were complications at birth, birth defects, `` ill-defined conditions,'' accidents and pneumonia and flu. As of Dec. 12, 1,291 cases of AIDS had been reported among infants and children under age 13 and an additional 325 cases in the 13-to-19-year group. Of those, 717 who were under 13 at the time of their diagnosis have already died, along with 174 who were adolescents when diagnosed. `` The official figures include only those children whose condition was reported to the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>,'' said a report from a task force headed by <PERSON> Novello </PERSON>. `` Probably for every child who meets the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> definition of AIDS, another two to 10 are infected with HIV. It is estimated that by 1991 there will be at least 10,000 to 20,000 HIV-infected children in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' HIV is the virus that causes AIDS, and health officials are growing increasingly concerned that a large majority of those infected eventually will develop AIDS and die. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report, requested by Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON>, D-Calif., said that even though the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>'s AIDS education budget increased from about $ 17 million in fiscal 1985 to nearly $ 210 million in 1988, `` its efforts to focus national attention on AIDS prevention were impaired by the slow implementation of key activities aimed at the general public. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> decided in May 1987 to designate the following October as `` AIDS Awareness and Prevention Month,'' but was unable to get clearance from the White House Domestic Policy Council _ a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> group _ for its plans to conduct a national AIDS information mailing to all households. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had made clear it thought such a mailing should be done, but had not explicitly required it. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> made a mailing mandatory the following year and the pamphlet `` Understanding AIDS'' went out to more than 100 million households last June. In conjunction with `` AIDS Awareness and Prevention Month'' in 1987, <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> contracted for production of 38 public service announcements on AIDS and distributed them to the major television networks on Sept. 30, 1987, the report said. However, it said there was only one airing by a network during the following month and only six the following months. When ads did air, they were not likely to be seen by many people. Between December 1987 and February 1988, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> reported, nearly 90 percent of all network-aired AIDS public service announcements were shown during non-primetime viewing hours. Nearly 60 percent were shown between 11 p.m. and 7 a.m., <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said.
