<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The economy expanded at a moderate 2.5 percent pace during the July-September quarter, the government reported Tuesday, but analysts said growth was rebounding and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> probably will nudge interest rates higher as a result. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said growth of the gross national product, the broadest measure of economic health, slowed during the third quarter from 3.0 percent in the 2nd quarter and 3.4 percent in the first three months of the year. The GNP, after adjusting for inflation, rose $ 24.2 billion to an annual rate of $ 4.01 trillion in the third quarter. The GNP figure for the third quarter, the slowest expansion pace since the final quarter of 1986, was a slight downward revision from a preliminary estimate of 2.6 percent issued a month ago. Most economists had been looking for a slight upward adjustment. The trend should be good news for <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> policy makers who want to curb economic growth to a range of 2 percent to 2.5 percent, which they believe is sustainable without increasing inflation. However, the government said the temporary effects of the summer drought, which shriveled crops and seared pastures, are masking the true strength of the economy in the final nine months of the year. Drought losses of $ 12.3 billion reduced the GNP growth rate by 0.9 percentage points in the second quarter, 0.5 percentage points in the third and will knock more than 1.0 percent off of fourth quarter rate. The growth rate in the final three months of this year, excluding the effects of the drought, will top 3 percent, most economists believe. In the first half of next year, assuming a return to normal farm production, the economy will be expanding at a rate between 3 percent and 4 percent, they say. `` What you're left with is an economy that is growing too fast to be acceptable to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> members fear that a GNP growth rate higher than the target range will strain factory capacity, leading to shortages and resulting price increases. Also, by boosting employment, the growth encourages employers to bid up wages. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s `` cure'' is higher interest rates designed to make it more expensive for consumers and businesses to spend. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> began nudging interest rates higher in late March, capping a series of tightening moves in August with a rise in the discount rate, the interest it charges on loans to member banks. When economic statistics for October and November made it clear that growth remained robust, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> responded last week by bumping up the federal funds rate, the rate banks charge each other for overnight loans, by a quarter of a percentage point to a range of 8 | percent to 8 ~ <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities dealer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the next tightening move likely will come in the first two weeks of next month, with another quarter point rise in the federal funds rate. `` I think the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will have to lean somewhat against those -LRB- strong growth -RRB- winds with a series of modest tightening steps,'' but it will delay raising the discount rate. `` If anything, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is in danger of underreacting.'' However, other economists, noting that consumer prices are rising at a 4.4 percent annual rate in 1988, the same as last year, say inflation fears are overstated. `` What we're afraid of is the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will get carried away next year and raise interest rates too high and keep them too high too long,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a forecasting firm in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. `` We might end up with a recession in late 1989 or early 1990.'' But <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> noted that a GNP price index, which measures price increases in what Americans are producing as opposed to what they are buying, shot up at an annual rate of 5.3 percent in the third quarter, the biggest jump in six years. That was up from a 5.0 percent rate in the second quarter. In an accompanying report, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said corporate profits after taxes advanced 3.9 percent in the third quarter after soaring 8.9 percent in the second quarter. An earlier estimate, which did not take into account profits by overseas subsidiaries of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations, had said third quarter profits rose only a slight 0.2 percent.
