<HEAD>Premadasa Declared Winner, Appeals For End to Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT typo in Sri Lanka.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto COL4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> was declared winner Tuesday of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s presidential election, and he appealed for an end to the killing that has crippled this tropical island nation. `` The ballots of the people have triumphed over the bullets of brutality,'' <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> said. `` The politics of terror has no place in the temple of democracy,'' he said. `` I will eradicate fear and suppression. I will restore law and order.'' <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s victory with slightly more than half of the votes ended a campaign marked by hundreds of slayings, which the government blames on the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a Sinhalese extremist group that opposed the balloting. Police said members of the group hacked and shot to death nine supporters of <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s party Tuesday in <LOCATION> Bandarawela </LOCATION>, 76 miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. A 9 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew was imposed on the nation of 16 million to prevent violence after the results were announced. `` I have an appeal to make to those who have still to join the democratic process,'' <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> said in a nationally televised address. `` Your participation will enable us to eradicate fear and poverty with greater speed.'' He also stretched a conciliatory hand to the two losing candidates, although an adviser to the runner-up, former Prime Minister <PERSON> Sirimavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>, said she was not accepting the final results. The intimidation campaign by the Sinhalese extremists kept many people from the polls Monday. Only 55 percent of 9.3 million eligible voters turned out to vote compared with 80 percent in the last presidential election six years ago. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> received 50.4 percent of the vote, followed by Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Sri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with 44.9 percent, according to election Commissioner <PERSON> Chandrananda </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>. He said no balloting took place in parts of eastern <LOCATION> Moneragala </LOCATION> district because no polling officers had arrived, but he added that the three candidates agreed not to make an issue out of it. Mrs. <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON> had no immediate comment. But <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponnambalam </PERSON>, a spokesman for the five-party <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION>' Alliance that backed her, said the candidate sent a letter to the Elections Commissioner `` requesting him not to announce results since she is not accepting the final count. When <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> takes over <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s most powerful government post Jan. 2, he will be working with a new <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, which was dissolved Tuesday by outgoing President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> has ruled for 11 years and was barred by the constitution from seeking a third term. Parliamentary elections are scheduled for Feb. 15. The president serves for six years and appoints the prime minister and other ministers. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said `` we look forward to working closely with President-elect <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> to strengthen further the warm relationship we have enjoyed with <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> under President <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>.'' `` The people and the leadership of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> have displayed laudable courage and determination in holding presidential elections in defiance of terrorist threats,'' the department said in a brief statement. The current cycle of violence in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, an island once famed as an idyllic tourist resort, dates from 1983, when the Tamil ethnic minority began its uprising against the majority <PERSON> Sinalhese </PERSON>. Nearly 10,000 people have been killed since then. With the help of neighboring <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the subcontinent's superpower and home to 60 million Tamils, <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> signed a peace accord in July 1987 aimed at ending the Tamil insurgency. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> opposed the plan despite being a top government official and boycotted the signing ceremony. The pact guaranteed some autonomy to the Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, and invited <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to help end the uprising by sending troops, which now total 47,000. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> vehemently opposes the pact, saying the government should not compromise with the Tamils. The <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tiger </ORGANIZATION> rebels seeking an independent state also oppose the accord, and are fighting Indian soldiers in the northeast. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> has called for the phased or immediate withdrawal of Indian troops, but dealing with the huge neighbor could prove difficult. Indian High Commissioner J.N. <PERSON> Dixit </PERSON> has indicated his country wo n't accept unilateral action. `` The peace pact was a bilateral one and the unilateral abrogation by one side will create an unprecedented situation,'' he said recently. `` As far as <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> is concerned, we are firmly committed to the accord.'' <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> also stressed his determination to fight poverty in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, where the annual per capital income is $ 360. He has proposed giving $ 75 a month to the poorest families, but has not explained how to pay for the program.
