<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> today blamed improperly loaded cargo for the crash of a commuter plane in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> last year that killed 18 people. The board said the <ORGANIZATION> Ryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> flight crew failed to properly oversee the loading of the craft and that so much of the cargo was loaded in the rear that the pilot lost control of the plane. `` The real responsibility rested with the crew, which is responsible for supervising the loading of the aircraft,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON>, acting chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>. `` For reasons I guess we'll never know, they failed in that function.'' The twin-engine turboprop crashed on approach to Homer Airport in Homer, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, on Nov. 23, 1987. Eighteen of the 21 people on board were killed. Investigators had believed that ice on the aircraft might have contributed to the accident, but the board said the ice `` did not cause but may have exacerbated the loss of control.'' The crash was <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Air </PERSON>'s 10th in eight years, and the company had been fined 10 months before the crash for record-keeping violations. While the board did not explicitly clear <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Air </PERSON> for any blame in the accident, it adopted no conclusions that the commuter airline was at fault. The staff report was adopted on a 4-1 vote, with board member <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> voting no because he first wanted to see changes in wording that were agreed to in the board's meeting.
