<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Christmas should be a hopping good time for Quasimodo, who'll make the leap from pet store prodigy to house pet for some lucky youngster. The rare red-eyed, albino bullfrog has lived at <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>'s shop for 18 months, greeting customers and entertaining hundreds of children. But this Christmas, Quasimodo is being adopted for the princely price of $ 59.97. At first, viewers may mistake Quasimodo for a plastic toy, because of his out-of-the-ordinary yellow color and his practice of sitting motionless for long periods. But underneath, he's all frog. Quasimodo's unusual color is due to a lack of sufficient pigmentation to make him the run-of-the-mill-pond brownish green. He was a highly unusual find for <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>, who bought Quasimodo from a wholesale dealer. `` It was unusual that he was found before he was eaten,'' he said. `` Most albino frogs stand out so much they are gobbled up by other predators. Somehow he survived long enough to get captured.'' The nearly 2-year-old frog is still growing, and in the security of his new family, he can be expected to live eight to 10 years, <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iron is discoloring the water in <LOCATION> Waterford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION>, and hairdressers say they're not the only ones who know for sure. Residents of the <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> community who shampoo with the rusty public water supply complain that it's turning their hair yellow, orange and even green, an undesireable shade even in this holiday season. `` What -LRB- the iron -RRB- is doing is depositing on blond hair or any type of hair and it builds up,'' said beauty salon owner <PERSON> Cyndi </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. `` I've had cases where the hair turns green.'' Some of the township's public wells contain iron levels six times higher than <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> guidelines, state and county officials said. The iron does n't pose any known health threats, but it makes the water taste bitter, smell bad, stain laundry and clog pipes. The township could end the problem by tying into <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s water network, according to a report issued last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Waterford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>.
