 The failures of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space program over the past 30 years are highlighted in an unusual exhibit. The exhibit at the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cosmosphere </LOCATION> and Space Center features the remains of the Mercury-Atlas I, the ill-fated, unmanned rocket that exploded less than one minute after liftoff on July 29, 1960. The remains were retrieved from the floor of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> more than 20 years ago and previously were housed in a museum in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. The exhibit, which opened Monday, also includes a backup unit for <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> response to the Soviet Sputnik. <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION>, launched Dec. 6, 1957, rose six inches and collapsed. But the display is not only about failures. `` This shows the difficulties we faced in getting man, and rockets, into space,'' said <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Ary </PERSON>, executive director of the space museum. There is a wall-sized mural of President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. An old RCA television sitting in a recreation of a 30-year-old livingroom plays <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s speech to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in which he proposed the Apollo moon-landing program. `` I believe that this nation should commit itself to achieving the goal before the decade is out of landing a man on the moon and returning him safely to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. A brief video called `` 39 Percent Success Rate'' provides a light look at some of the 80 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unmanned satellite launches, 49 of which ended in failure. A block house blast window _ a 250-pound chunk of glass that shielded the launch crew at <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATIO