<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has been shaken by internal turmoil in recent months, raising concerns about the powerful pro-Israeli lobby's relations with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and its ability to protect the Jewish state from the fallout of strained relations with the administration. The latest setback to befall <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> is last week's resignation of its legislative director, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloomfield </PERSON>, the organization's respected and popular liaison with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> It follows several unfavorable news reports about the generally low-profile group, based partly on documents supplied by disgruntled <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> employees. Included among the allegations were that <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> violated its mandate by supporting candidates in the recent congressional elections and that it mapped out a campaign to smear the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Observers and insiders differ on whether <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>'s problems are a result of personality clashes or a reflection of fundamental policy differences within the organization, which is viewed as possessing almost mythical clout in this power-conscious city. But all agree it could not have come at a worse time for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the American Jewish community. The paternalistic alliance between <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> is being strained by last week's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to launch talks with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The decision, taken after <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> declared he recognized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist, is viewed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s leadership as betraying a promise given 13 years ago not to deal with its arch-enemy. U.S.-Israel ties will be put to a further test in the months ahead by requests from <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> for millions of dollars worth of arms sales. There are indications the administration of President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may be more inclined to acquiesce to those requests, which were turned down under congressional pressure in recent years. Jewish leaders also are concerned that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his chief of staff, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, who is of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> ancestry, may be less committed to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s security than the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, and especially in comparison with outgoing Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. `` It's now more important than ever that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> remain committed to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., who works closely with <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> and strongly supports the $ 3 billion annual <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign aid to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> and others in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who work closely with <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> say they perceive a shift from the organization's emphasis on lobbying the legislative branch to lobbying the executive branch. Others charge <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>'s leadership, especially Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Asher </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>, with a pro-Republican bias that damns them in the eyes of the Democratic majority on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` The partisanship that is perceived as creeping into <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>'s decision-making will hurt them in the long run,'' said Democratic Rep. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, who has been instrumental in opposing arms sales to the Arabs `` They have to understand that the real bedrock of support for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Administrations come and go. We're pretty constant and reliable,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. The perception of <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>'s partisan leanings appears due in part to an eight-year Republican administration which has been warmly supportive of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. For example, <PERSON> Jewish </PERSON> leaders say they were reluctant to criticize <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s decision to reverse the ban on talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> because of his traditionally staunch support for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The perception is further highlighted because it contrasts sharply with American Jews' traditional support for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Jews voted 2-to-1 in favor of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the November elections. Especially disturbing to <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> supporters in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was its reaction to the administration's request last summer for 40 F-18 jet fighters worth $ 1.8 billion for <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>, following <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s lead, contended that the sale to the moderate <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nation did not threaten <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> security <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who led the fight against the sale and counted on <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>'s backing, was angry `` They lost sight of the fact that in the long run this will be harmful to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` There's a legitimate debate about whether we're selling weapons to the <LOCATION> Arabs </LOCATION> as a bribe or whether we have a coherent policy toward them. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Amitay </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer who was <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director from 1974 to 1980, cautioned the lobby's leadership about bypassing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and trying to influence the administration directly. `` It's not very sophisticated of them,'' he said. `` Anyone who knows how this city works knows it's wrong.'' <ORGANIZATION> AIPAC </ORGANIZATION> leaders declined to be interviewed, saying the organization's low profile is essential for its behind-the-scenes effectiveness. But privately officials said the organization was n't moving away from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, noting that it is adding one congressional lobbyist to its list of five. They also denied any Republican leanings, noting that some of their senior board members are known Democrats.
</TEXT>
