<HEAD>Former Ohio Congressman Named to Deficit Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, selected by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday for the high-level commission studying the deficit problem, is a Democrat who has been friends with the president-elect since they were classmates at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> long ago. <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, 65, was a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> congressman from <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION> for 26 years before his defeat in <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1980 landslide. <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, whose nickname is `` Lud'' from his middle name of <PERSON> Ludlow </PERSON>, is now president of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION>, a lobbying group which represents the country's largest banks. He is considered one of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s oldest and closest friends. At <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, they were members of the secret society, Skull and Bones. Asked once to describe his friend, <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> said, `` He has spent a lifetime thinking in conventional terms, never reaching beyond them, never even wanting to.'' In announcing <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>'s appointment to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he expected to benefit from <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>'s `` counsel and his candor'' on the commission. `` I have had the privilege of knowing <PERSON> Lud </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> for over 40 years,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in a statement. `` He understands the full range of national issues _ from housing, to energy, to the problems of our cities.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision to put his long-time friend on the panel gave supporters of the commssion hope that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may take its recommendations more seriously. During the campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> derided the commission as a stalking horse for tax increases. <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, considered a liberal Democrat while in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, served as ranking member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and was also considered an expert on energy problems. Like <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> fought in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> during World War II and then entered <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> to resume his education. He received his undergraduate degree in 1948 and then earned a law degree by attending night classes at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toledo </ORGANIZATION> law school. He practiced law with his father and brother in <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION> before joining the staff of Radio Free <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1952, where he served as assistant director for special projects for two years. He was elected to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1954, serving in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> where his great-grandfather, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, had served during the Civil War. The great-grandfather had also been governor of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> when the area was a territory.
