<SECOND>AM-China-Cambodia,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Says It Will Stop Aid To Insurgents If Vietnam Withdraws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Tuesday announced it would stop aiding the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and other <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance forces as soon as <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> withdraws its troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The statement, which appeared in the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>, was a further indication that <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s policy toward <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> has softened. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s premier, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>, made the statement at a news conference Monday with journalists from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> covering Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s visit. According to the report, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said `` if <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> withdraws from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, all parties, including <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, should stop aiding elements in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.'' In addition, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said, `` in order to calm the fears of the international community, as <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> withdraws, we will decrease our military assistance to the resistance forces.'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in December 1978 and unseated the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, who had ruled the country from 1975. More than a million people are believed to have died during their bloody reign. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the capitalist countries of <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the West support a three-party resitance coalition comprised of forces loyal to Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sann </PERSON>, a Western-leanding politician. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has said it will leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by 1990 and will turn the war over to the government of <PERSON> Heng </PERSON> <PERSON> Samrin </PERSON>, which it installed in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> in 1979. But the Cambodian forces are weak and there are widespread fears the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> will return to power after <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> pulls out its forces. On Monday, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> announced another troop withdrawal. The troops were among the 50,000 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> says are being sent home this year in its seventh annual partial pullout. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> says the current withdrawal will leave 50,000 troops in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s position on <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> has been evolving over the last few months as its relationship with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s main backer, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, improves Initially, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> demanded <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> withdraw completely from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> before <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would even consider ceasing military aid. It also had expressed close support of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. Over the summer, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> moved noticeably away from the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and began backing a <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> government headed by <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>. In November, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said once the Vietnamese produced a timetable for the withdrawal, `` then the military assistance to all the four parties in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> must and also can be graduwlly reduced and even totally stopped.'' Tuesday's announcement marked a further revising of the Chinese position because it dropped the demand for a timetable.
