<HEAD>US Skeptical on Vietnam's Withdrawal Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> expressed skepticism Tuesday that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> will fulfill its pledge to withdraw 50,000 troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> before the end of the year. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> contends that its commitment is being met with the withdrawal of 18,000 troops this week. But <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials insisted that even if the Vietnamese estimate of the size of the ongoing pullback is accurate, it would only bring the total for the year to between 28,000 and 33,000 troops. While welcoming this week's troop withdrawal, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said, `` We remain skeptical that the 50,000 pledge will be met.'' She estimated the current Vietnamese troop commitment to <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> at between 90,000 and 100,000, down from about 120,000 at the start of the year. `` Since we believe <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s illegal occupation is the root cause of the conflict, we continue to urge <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> to issue a precise timetable for the withdrawal of its remaining troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> during 1989 and to allow for the verification of their withdrawal,'' she said. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has indicated all its troops in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> will be withdrawn by 1990. Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said once all Vietnamese forces are withdrawn and there is an acceptable political settlement in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be prepared to normalize relations with <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>. Some previous administration statements had conditioned the establishment of normal ties with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s cooperation in accounting for the estimated 1,700 American servicemen listed as missing from the Vietnam War, but there was no such link included in Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON>'s statement Tuesday. A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said Tuesday the MIA issue was being dealt with separately, and he cited statements by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and other senior officials suggesting there was no explicit link between the MIA issue and normal relations with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. But last July, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> linked diplomatic ties with <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> both to a <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> settlement and to `` a resolution of the POW-MIA issue which, if left unsettled, will continue to divide our peoples.'' Asked whether the POW-MIA condition had been dropped, Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said, `` We have been stressing that it is the complete withdrawal of all Vietnamese forces in the context of an acceptable settlement in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> which will be the determining factor.'' <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s political future following the Vietnamese withdrawal is highly uncertain. The pro-Hanoi government in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> has been fighting against three rebel groups, two of which are backed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The third is the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, which is widely accused of having engaged in mass genocide when it ruled <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> between 1975 and 1978. An alternate approach to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> was outlined in a report released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Aspen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a private research group. The report recommended the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> take `` graduated'' diplomatic steps toward <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> if its troops are withdrawn from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> prior to a <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> settlement. These steps should include the establishment of small diplomatic missions in each other's capital and adjustments in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade embargo against <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, the report said. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> is one of a handful of countries with which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does not maintain diplomatic relations.
