PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> would testify in person had been one reason the trial dragged on over seven weeks even though only eight hours of testimony was actually heard, spread over three days. Courtroom action came to a halt in mid-November when the defense called <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> as its first witness. Attorneys for the governor argued he should not have to appear, and the judge eventually agreed with them and let the governor testify by giving a deposition in his office. That delay was only one of several in the trial, which first had been set to begin March 11. <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> was removed from his seat in the <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last month after being sentenced to four years in federal prison on an unrelated extortion conviction. All 14 legislators were charged with second-degree trespassing, which carries a maximum penalty of three months' imprisonment and a $ 500 fine upon conviction. The defendants claim they were protected by legislative immunity during the protest and that no trespass on state property occurred since they never got over the fence. The prosecution contended trespassing occurred when their hands gripped the fence.
