<HEAD>Defense Opens By Attacking Ms. Nussbaum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers for <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, accused of murdering his illegally adopted daughter, opened their defense Tuesday with an assault on the credibility and character of <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s chief accuser and former live-in companion. Police Officer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Andry </PERSON> testified he had found a woman who looked just like <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> drinking a beer and smoking in a stranger's car while <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, the 6-year-old girl the couple raised, was unconscious in the family apartment nearby. He said he was convinced it was, indeed, Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>. In seven days of graphic testimony, Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> testified that she never left the house after <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> fell unconscious, sometime around 7 p.m. on Nov. 1, 1987. The prosecution maintains <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> was unconscious because <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> had struck her before going out to dinner with a friend. `` The focus of this trial has shifted from <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> to <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s lawyer, <LOCATION> Ira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, said outside the courtroom. He said there were unexplained bruises on <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s body, and implied that the defense will suggest Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> was responsible. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, 47, a disbarred lawyer, is charged with second-degree murder in the child's death. He denies that he hit the child, but Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> testified that he told her he had struck <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>. <PERSON> Andry </PERSON> said that he found Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> sitting, slumped down, in a car near the couple's <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> apartment around 8:40 p.m. on Nov. 1, 1987. He said he asked the woman if the car was hers. She said no, and he told her to get out. She did. `` Her nose was distorted like it was messed up somehow. Her eyes looked like they were dazed,'' he said. The officer's description of the woman fit the description of Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, a former children's book author and editor, at the time of her arrest Nov. 2, 1987. Charges against her were later dropped after prosecutors concluded she was too severely battered by <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> to have prevented <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s death. `` Is there any question as you sit here today that the woman you saw sitting in the car on West 10th Street was <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>?'' <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> asked. `` There's no question about it,'' the officer replied. Earlier in the day, the prosecution rested after presenting 39 witnesses since the trial began more than eight weeks ago. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> denied a defense request to throw out all charges against <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>. He did say he was inclined to drop one charge against <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, endangering the welfare of the 16-month-old boy police found in <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s apartment the morning they took the unconscious <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> to a hospital The boy was illegally adopted, just as <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> was. He has since been returned to his biological mother. <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> also said he would also instruct the jury to consider two lesser homicide counts not included in the indictment against <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>. They are second-degree manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> is also charged with second-degree murder, first-degree manslaughter and endangering the welfare of a minor with respect to <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>. The prosecution's last witness, Dr. <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> McHugh </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> was a victim of child abuse. She based her opinion on medical and autopsy reports and color photographs taken of the child. She said that findings of multiple bruises, the child's poor hygiene and the brain hemorrhage <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> suffered were consistent with child abuse.
