<HEAD>New Centers to Help US Firms Compete</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government named institutions in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> on Tuesday to serve as the first three regional centers to help funnel scientific advancements to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses so they can better compete against Japanese and other trade rivals. `` We've been winning the Nobel prizes and the Japanese have been winning the profits,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, a sponsor of the legislation which established the program. He spoke at a news conference organized by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to announce the choice of the three non-profit centers, from among 36 applicants. Commerce Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON> said there will be additional centers, but he was uncertain whether three or five more will be sought in the next federal budget. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has authorized 12 centers altogether, but provided money only for the first three: $ 12 million for the year ending next Sept. 30, to be matched by money from indidividual states and the institutions concerned. The first centers will be at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Rensselaer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Troy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and at the <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. `` The centers will help smaller firms take advantage of some of