n a year in federal block grants to states, it basically subsidizes employer costs in training disadvantaged and retraining dislocated workers. A graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> with a law degree from <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Guttman </PERSON> worked in various staff jobs in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> from 1956 to 1970. From 1970 to 1981, he was a specialist on social legislation for the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> also formally announced that <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>, 46, a former correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, will be his press secretary. That decision had been reported earlier.
