<HEAD>UNICEF: Debt Crisis Killing Children in Developing World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A half-million children died last year because their Third World countries slashed social welfare spending when faced with unprecedented debt, <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday in its annual report. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> executive director, urged leaders of industrialized and developing nations to convene a summit to deal with the crisis. He made the appeal in <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION>'s annual report, `` The State of the World's Children,'' which he formally released at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> news conference telecast live to 40 nations. The 500,000 children he mentioned represented only a fraction of the child deaths in 1987 recorded by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Children's Fund. `` Three million children died last year because they did n't have 50 cents worth of vaccine in them,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said. Half these deaths occurred in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Among a few bright spots he highlighted were vaccination programs in two war-torn countries. `` In <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, in the midst of war, they have been able to stop the war long enough to immunize their children,'' he said. Failure to vaccinate children results not only from the debt crises but from war, ignorance, lack of health workers and rugged terrains isolating people from medical care. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said that for children these were the best and worst of times. `` They are the worst of times because after 35 years of progress, a significant percentage of mankind _ 900 million people _ is now sliding backward into poverty,'' he said. `` It's the best of times, because low-cost ways -LRB- of preventing children's deaths -RRB- are becoming increasingly available.'' These methods include vaccination against diseases such as measles, tetanus and whooping cough. Others are oral rehydration programs, using inexpensive salt solutions that combat diarrhea, chief killer of small children in many impoverished nations. One of the most alarming trends he noted was that 16 nations made less progress against child mortality last year than they were making a decade ago because their debt-burdened governments have had to cut back on social spending. `` By far the heaviest consequences are being borne by the children,'' said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. `` For these 16 countries alone, the number of child deaths in the last 12 months is approximately 650,000 more than would have been the case if the 1970-80 rate of decline in under-five mortality had continued.'' The 16 nations cited by <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> are <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Benin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Togo </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> report said `` the developing world is now transferring $ 20 billion a year more to the rich nations than it receives in new aid and loans.'' Developing nations owe $ 1.2 trillion to foreign governments, private banks and development funds. `` It's clear that in the'80s, private contributions for development have doubled while government assistance has declined,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said. `` The governments should increase their aid, but there is also the question of public opinion insisting that they do so.'' Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, in a pre-recorded preface to <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>'s telecast, said: `` Not only are the present needs of children neglected but in our greedy growth to development, we are threateing to mortgage their future.'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen whose Canadian forebears served as doctors and medical missionaries in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, called for a world summit to focus attention and seek solutions to the problems of children. `` Why should n't political leaders of both developing and developed countries have a world summit on children?'' he asked. `` To reach the unreached, our conclusion is that one must first reach the unreached's leaders.''
