<HEAD>Report Says Press Freedom Damaged in Democratic Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tabloids, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Press freedom was undermined in 1988 by governments in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and other democracies, which should set examples of tolerance, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said in a report released Tuesday. It called the development the `` most worrying aspect'' of its annual `` World Press Freedom Review,'' which surveyed the press in 82 countries on six continents. `` The hopes and encouragement of nations which are on their way toward more freedom and who rely on an example from countries with a democratic system, an open society and freedom, must not be crushed by governments in the free world,'' director <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Galliner </PERSON> wrote in an introduction to the report. The institute, which has offices in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, is an independent body representing 2,000 publishers and editors in more than 60 countries. Its report cited these examples of official interference: _ <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> `` continued its efforts to limit public access to information held by the American government. _ The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the conviction of a former intelligence analyst for giving satellite photographs of a Soviet ship to a British magazine <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Loring </PERSON> <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> is serving two years in prison. _ Under the new Canada-U.S. Free Trade Agreement restricts Canadian journalists working in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to those with university degrees and three years experience It was the first time the rule, already part of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law, was `` enshrined in an international accord.'' _ Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s British government tried to ban publication of extracts from the `` Spycatcher'' memoirs of former intelligence agent <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> Newspapers defeated the government in court. _ <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> barred radio or television interviews with 11 groups involved in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, including <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>, the legal political wing of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, in the `` most drastic action taken against British broadcasters in peacetime. _ Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the world's most populous democracy, agreed only at the last minute to withdraw legislation shifting the onus of proof of defamation from plaintiff to journalist _ A court court in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> ordered a journalist to reveal his sources _ <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> suspended three <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> newspapers for up to 45 days and shut down the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, `` a prime source of information for the foreign press. Elsewhere, the report found, `` the media under dictatorships remained all too predictably under lock and key.'' In <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> there were violent assaults on 24 foreign and Chilean journalists while five journalists in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> were forced to leave the country following passage of an anti-terrorist law, it said. <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> cracked down on their press, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> continued to pressure the media and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> reasserted control on open discussion and suppressed negative news. South Africa closed two church newspapers for three months and the country's most outspoken anti-apartheid paper, the Weekly Mail, was suspended for four weeks. On the other hand, the report said, many visible and invisible restrictions were lifted on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s press, and in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> economic and political liberalizations extended to the media. In the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the report declared, `` it seems that anything goes'' these days. `` No cow, it is tempting to believe, is too sacred to slaughter. In fact, however, matters are not as simple as that. ... We should never forget that glasnost -LRB- openness -RRB- began as, and remains, a policy guided from above.''
