<HEAD>UCSF Scientists Find Both Types of AIDS Virus In One Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> have isolated the AIDS virus and its African cousin from the same patient, showing both can infect the same individual, scientists report. Previous studies had suggested the two viruses could infect the same person, but the new study confirms it by isolating the viruses themselves, researchers said. In a tatement from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, researchers said the finding indicates that individuals infected with one strain should continue to take precautions against becoming infected by the second. The combination of both strains might speed up damage to the immune system, they said. The work appears in the Dec. 17 issue of <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lancet </LOCATION>, a British medical journal. Researchers from <ORGANIZATION> UCSF </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> reported isolating HIV-1, the virus that causes AIDS in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and the African HIV-2 virus from a 37-year-old woman from the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. The viruses cause a variety of diseases, including acquired immune deficiency syndrome. AIDS from HIV-1 has killed about 45,000 people so far in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but HIV-2 has been found here in only one West African patient visiting the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The HIV-2 strain has been primarily limited to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The study was led by <ORGANIZATION> UCSF </ORGANIZATION> postdoctoral researcher <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> A. <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>, professor of medicine and an investig