<HEAD>Quebec Decision on Signs Revives Regional, Linguistic Tensions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th `Environment Minister' to include two
other resignations. PICKS up 5th pvs: Bourassa based his ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Regional and linguistic antagonisms that have threatened unity throughout <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s history are reviving because Quebec will not comply with a ruling that it allow the posting of signs in English. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said last week the predominantly French-speaking province is justified in making sure French predominates on signs but can not prevent the use of other languages. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>, the provincial premier, angered both English speakers and militants from the majority with his compromise last Sunday: French must remain the only language on outdoor signs but other languages can be used indoors so long as French predominates. Environment Minister <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, one of four English speakers in <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>'s Cabinet, resigned Tuesday and said: `` In my beliefs, rights are rights are rights. There are no partial rights. There are no indoor-outdoor rights.'' Two of the other English speakers _ Public Security Minister <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> and Communications Minister <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON> _ quit later Tuesday. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> based his decision on a clause put into the constitution by Western provinces as a protection against federal power, which allows provinces or the national government to override a court decision. The resumption of divisiveness in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> followed four years of general calm that made possible the 1987 <LOCATION> Meech </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> constitutional agreement recognizing <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> as a `` distinct society.'' Only eight of the 10 provinces have ratified the accord, named for the place in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> where it was signed. Premier <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Filmon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> said Monday he no longer would push for legislative approval in his Western province because of <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>'s action. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, on the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coast, is the other province yet to ratify the agreement. <PERSON> Filmon </PERSON> described the <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> decision as a `` national tragedy'' and called for a national conference of provincial leaders to persuade the French-speaking province to accept the court decision. Which language can be used on signs is a volatile and symbolic issue <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s French speakers _ 81 percent of the population _ consider essential to preserving their linguistic and cultural heritage. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>'s plan prohibits languages other than French on signs both outdoors and in such places as shopping malls and interiors of public transportation facilities. An editorial Tuesday in The Globe and Mail of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> said: `` What now? Almost certainly a hardening of hearts, a less generous attitude, an unwillingness to spend precious political capital on bilingualism and francophones, tougher questioning of the primordiality granted to <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s concerns; in sum, a quiet, unspectacular but undeniable backlash that will do us all no good.'' La Presse, a widely read <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> daily, said <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> chose `` the best compromise under the circumstances.'' It said either continuing the ban on any language other than French or allowing bilingual signs everywhere `` would have been to scorn Quebec reality, both historic and present.'' In 1985, <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> campaigned for election on a platform that included easing language restrictions on signs. Critics say he could have avoided angering militants if he had acted soon after the election instead of responding to a court ruling three years later. A crowd of 10,000 or more attended a rally Sunday in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> demanding no changes in the language law, which was passed in 1977 by the separatist Parti Quebecois gpverment. Power in the province shifted from the English-speaking minority to the French speakers in the 1970s. Separatist sentiment abated after the language law was passed and Quebec's voters rejected a sovereignty in a 1980 referendum.
