<HEAD>Energy Department to Negotiate Legally Binding Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will negotiate with the state to reach a legally binding agreement to clean up a federally owned uranium processing plant, a spokesman said Tuesday. The decision was made late Tuesday, said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Elmets </PERSON>, a spokesman for the department in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. A day earlier, he had said federal officials were still considering whether the agreement should be in the form of a consent decree that would be enforceable through federal courts. News reports indicating that the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was backing away from a consent decree had prompted state Attorney General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Celebrezze </PERSON> to insist that <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> had a commitment that federal officials should honor. When state officials announced a $ 50 million federal agreement on Nov. 22 to clean up the <ORGANIZATION> Portsmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gaseous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diffusion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Piketon </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> they said it could serve as a model for dealing with contamination at nuclear weapons plants around the country. <PERSON> Elmets </PERSON> said the department reached its decision after discussions with <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> officials and consultations with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s operations office in <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION> `` This decision was based on the same factors that influenced our decision on two earlier consent decrees in regard to <LOCATION> Fernald </LOCATION> litigation,'' <PERSON