TION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and some of its members approved of talking to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> views the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> as a terrorist group. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told the delegates that if the party did not approve the agreement at the meeting he would go to President <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> and give up the mandate he was given to form a new government. Such a move would throw <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s political system into a state of confusion. <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> had given <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, whose party slightly edged out Labor in Nov. 1 elections, until Dec. 26 to form a new government. Labor Cabinet ministers, meanwhile, approved the coalition pact Tuesday. The agreement will be submitted Wednesday to the party's 1,000-member central committee <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said formation of the new coalition would spell defeat for the proposed `` Who is a Jew'' legislation that was vehemently opposed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews. That prospect touched off wrangling between <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and the four religious parties, who originally demanded the legislation and now threaten to stay out of the coalition. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> hopes to include the religious parties to make it more difficult for Labor to bring down the government should an impasse occur. <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Peretz </PERSON> of the Ultra-Orthodox Shas party accused <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> of breaking his pledges. `` He promised us and signed an agreement to help change the Law of Return,'' he said. The Law of Return grants automatic Israeli citizenship to all Jews, and the amendment would require Orthodox approval of all conversions to <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews feel the legislation will divide the Jewish community. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> were united in standing up to the `` common danger'' _ Arab demands for creation of an independent Palestinan state. `` There is a common danger to all of us, the establishment of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state. Both Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> see it as a danger, and the government will deal with it in a unified effort,'' he said. Although fear of too much influence by the religious parties had already sparked public support for another unity government, the latest agreement also was spurred by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision last week to open a dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> aides said they wanted to present a unified front against the move by their greatest ally. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told reporters the new government guidelines mean `` there will be no negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>.'' The decision to ban talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> puts <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> increasingly out of step with the rest of the international community, and could strain relations with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which provides $ 3 billion a year in economic and military aid to the Jewish state. Israeli officials said the new government would give top priority in the next two months to devising a peace formula that will be an acceptable alternative to dealing with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. One official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the guidelines call for talks based on the 1978 Camp David accords which envision limited autonomy for Palestinians and the participation of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> in the peace process. There will be few new faces in the new government. Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> will each control 10 seat