<HEAD>Rebels' General Strike Paralyzes Peruvian City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Maoist rebels cut transportation to a trickle Tuesday and shut down nearly all schools and offices in this important highland city in a general strike which they threatened to enforce with weapons. Scores of police and soldiers patrolled <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>'s nearly empty streets, but no reports emerged of violence or other guerrilla activity. It was the second so-called `` armed strike'' declared by the <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas in recent weeks. They paralyzed <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION>, their stronghold about 100 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>, for a week in late November with a similar strike. The rebels called the three-day strike in <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION>, 125 miles east of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, on Monday. The state government was quoted as saying Tuesday's strike had no impact. <PERSON> Abilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, the chief administrative officer of <LOCATION> Junin </LOCATION> state, said activity was normal throughout the state, according to a dispatch by the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> Andina </ORGANIZATION>. However, reporters for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and other media said nearly everyone stayed indoors, apparently in fear of guerrilla reprisals. The strike came a day after <PERSON> Favio </PERSON> <PERSON> Llerena </PERSON>, deputy to <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, said dozens of small-town mayors and farming hamlet officials across the state resigned after receiving death threats by the rebel group. For two years, <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION> and the surrounding <LOCATION> Mantaro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> valley, an important mining and agricultural area, have been targets of the Shining Path insurgency to topple <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s elected government and install a Marxist state. Officials say the violence is part of the guerrillas' overall goal of weakening <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> by fomenting political and economic chaos to pave the way for the rebels to seize power. `` The <LOCATION> Mantaro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> is practically taken over by the Shining Path, and there seems to be no way to defend it,'' former Industry Minister <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arteaga </PERSON> said over the weekend. Authorities declared a state of emergency throughout <LOCATION> Junin </LOCATION> a month ago as attacks increased dramatically on villages, power installations, railroads, bridges and large cooperative farms. Parts of eight states with more than half the nation's 21 million people are under emergency measures that give the military wide-ranging powers to police and govern. The capital, <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, is under the regulations. The government says the Shining Path insurgency has claimed more than 12,000 lives and caused damage of more than $ 10 billion, four times the amount of the nation's yearly exports.
