<HEAD>``Sally'' and ``Prince,'' Two Plays by Charles Fuller, Open
Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Credit playwright <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> with setting up an ambitious project for himself _ a cycle of five plays dealing with the black experience in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from the Civil War to the turn of the century. But his ambitions have gotten the best of him, at least in the first two of these historical dramas, called `` Sally'' and `` Prince,'' which arrived over the weekend at off-Broadway's <ORGANIZATION> Negro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ensemble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. The plays, both set during the Civil War, are sketchy historical melodramas, long on plot and short on poetry or power. They reiterate the same themes, particularly about freedom or the lack of it for blacks, first under the slavemasters of the Old South and then under the economic overlords of the North. The plays say they traded one serfdom for another. The subject is discussed early on in `` Sally,'' which had its world premiere last summer in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>. Despite its title, the play deals mostly with a group of black Union soldiers who are forced to take a pay cut and earn less than their white counterparts. Some are defiant and pay the price with their lives. Others accept it and pay a different kind of penalty. One who acquiesces is <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Logan </LOCATION>, an ambitious black soldier who is the most interesting character in both plays. His dilemma _ to follow the Army or revel in his newly won freedom _ merits most of your attention. It is <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>'s survival that <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> chronicles in these two dramas, and I suspect the man will turn up in other plays in this series. You do n't need to see both of the first two dramas to understand his character, but it helps. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s persuasive, even noble, performance as <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> also helps It's a portrayal that deepens in the second play as <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> tries to deal with the dislocation and disorientation of the newly freed slaves. These intentions get sidetracked by a lot of peripheral events, directed by <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> and acted by the rest of the large cast at a feverish pace. There are plenty of gunshots, a stabbing or two and some heavy-handed attempts at sexual humor. The dialogue is often flat, more concerned with recounting events than illuminating character. Consider the first play, the weaker of the two evenings of drama. Although she is the title character, <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> remains the most elusive person on stage. Tragic things happen to her _ her husband is poisoned, her son is killed by rebel troops, her affair with <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> ends malevolently _ but throughout her troubles, we never get to know the woman. <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Shay </PERSON>, a fine actress, is stymied by the underwritten role. Another good performer, <PERSON> Hattie </PERSON> <PERSON> Winston </PERSON>, has a better time of it in `` Prince,'' where she plays <PERSON> Lu </PERSON>, an indominable camp follower who also manages to live _ and profit _ through the war. In `` <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>,'' the focus switches from military to civilian, the ex-slaves who have to work the cotton fields for new masters from the North. These new employers _ a church group formed to help ex-slaves _ may seem more benevolent, at first, but their rule becomes just as tyrannical. The action takes place on a gray, utilitarian setting by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> McClennahan </PERSON>. It's simple but effective, allowing the fast-moving action to unfold quickly and with a minimum of fuss. In many ways, <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>'s plays tackle the same themes as <PERSON> August </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s Come and Gone,'' the story of ex-slaves coming to terms with their past. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s drama contains some haunting and painful but strangely beautiful images. `` Sally'' and `` Prince'' paint much more literal pictures. We'll have to wait for the next three plays to see if <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>'s vision is more fully realized.
</TEXT>
