<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday threw out the convictions of a habitual offender who was sentenced to 32 years in prison after he tried to get a refund for an electric razor without a receipt. The court, in a 4-1 decision, struck down the attempted theft and habitual criminal convictions of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> and ordered <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> discharged from <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> State Prison. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 49, was sentenced to two years in prison in 1985 for attempting to get a refund for a $ 42.96 Remington razor at three <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> stores. Under the state's habitual offender law, a fixed term of 30 years was added to the sentence because of <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s earlier convictions on auto banditry and drug charges Prosecutors argued at his <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> trial that <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> attempted `` to exert unauthorized control'' over one store's profit margin by creating the false impression he had purchased the razor there. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> concluded that in order to prove <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> was trying to create a false impression, the state needed to prove <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> had n't purchased the razor at the store. There was no evidence to demonstrate where the razor was purchased, the court said. `` Without that crucial element of proof, every citizen engaging in a simple refund transaction would risk criminal penalties,'' Chief Justice <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> wrote for the court. `` Some citizens such as those seeking to return gifts simply do not know where the item was originally purchased.'' Court records show that in November 1978, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> took the razor to a Hook's Drug store in <LOCATION> Mooresville </LOCATION> and later to a Hook's in <LOCATION> Martinsville </LOCATION> to get a refund. The package had a Hook's price tag on it, but employees refused to give <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> a refund because of a store policy requiring receipts for returned merchandise. He then went to a <PERSON> Danner </PERSON>'s store in <LOCATION> Martinsville </LOCATION> and presented the razor, without a price tag, for a refund. Hook's employees, suspicious about <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s behavior, had alerted <PERSON> Danner </PERSON>'s employees of his earlier attempts to get a refund. Employees at the <PERSON> Danner </PERSON>'s store called police when <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> showed up and stalled until police arrived to arrest <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, court records show. <PERSON> Danner </PERSON>'s also would have denied a refund under its no-receipt, no-refund policy. The long gap between his arrest and final sentencing occurred because <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> left the courtroom during his trial and remained at large for four years, according to court records.
