<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Your football team punted the playoffs, relatives are descending for the holidays and network TV is cluttered with junk.' T is the season to give thanks that you paid your cable bill For <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> has a nice little out-of-season movie this month, `` Dead Solid Perfect,'' an adaptation of <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>' novel of the same name about life on the links. What better time of year to be delivered from gray winter landscapes to the land of greens, fairways, sandtraps and perpetual short sleeves? `` Dead Solid Perfect'' is dead solid funny and a nice little love story to boot. It premiered last week, but you can still catch it tonight, Friday and next Tuesday. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Quaid </PERSON> -RRB- is a diamond-in-the-rough golfer, hustling bets on the side so he can afford to get to the next tournament. Enter <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> `` Bad Hair'' Wimberly -LRB- Jack Warden -RRB-, a hustler with more money than he knows what to do with, but a nasty slice he'll never be able to buy off So he buys <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>, becoming his sponsor on the tour. Exit Beverly -LRB- <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrold </PERSON> -RRB-, <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s intelligent wife, tired of hanging out with jerks like Bad Hair and dragging herself around the country to watch <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> cuss and sling golf clubs in disgust. Forget `` Caddyshack.'' This is the definitive golf movie of the'80s. Director <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, who co-wrote the screenplay with <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, does for the links what <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON> did for pool in `` The Color of Money.'' <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> successfully teamed on `` <LOCATION> Baja </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>'' for <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year. The music is by <ORGANIZATION> Tangerine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dream </ORGANIZATION>, and the theme song is sung by <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Vera </PERSON>. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> co-stars as Spec, <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s caddy, a talented golfer himself who stays in the background rather than challenge the racism of the sponsorship game. At one point, as <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> is preparing for a big tournament, Spec warns <PERSON> Bad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hair </PERSON>, `` Give him one word of advice, and I'll burn down your mansion and marry your daughter.'' <PERSON> Brett </PERSON> <PERSON> Cullen </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s friend, <PERSON> Donny </PERSON> <PERSON> Smithern </PERSON>, a successful young pro who gets recognized in restaurants, cheats on his good ol' gal wife -LRB- <PERSON> DeLane </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> -RRB- and waxes phony pious in TV interviews. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> is one of a handful of male authors around who can write realistic women. He gives his female characters a sense of humor without making them just sound like men. `` Good ol' Donny,'' <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> sneers at one point, `` he'll always be there when he needs you.'' After <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> leaves <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>, he takes up with <PERSON> Janie </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Corinne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bohrer </PERSON> -RRB-, a bimbo savant who chucks her job as a bartender to accompany him on the tour. At first, he plays well, and it's party time. But <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> warns <PERSON> Janie </PERSON> during an R-rated romp in their hotel room. `` It's not always this fun. Sometimes I play bad.'' `` So do I,'' <PERSON> Janie </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> starts playing really badly after he gets shook up by running into <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> and a new beau at a restaurant. <PERSON> Janie </PERSON> gamely tries to trade insults with <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> and spe