<HEAD>Peronists on the Move Again in Argentina</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, implanted in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> as the voice of the workers and the poor by <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> four decades ago, is in a resurgence it hopes will bring victory in presidential elections set for May. It has been out of power for 12 years. Virtually every poll gives <PERSON> Peronist </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, a colorful provincial governor, a commanding lead over the candidate of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON>. Provincial and congressional elections last year reversed <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> setbacks in 1983, when civilian government was restored after nearly eight years of military dictatorship during which <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> politicians, including <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, were jailed, <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> teachers were dismissed from universities and labor leaders were arrested and executed. In September 1987, Peronist candidates swept 17 of the country's 22 provinces, including <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, the biggest The party's inroads in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> eliminated the Radical's majority `` In 1983, it was n't <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> against <PERSON> Luder </PERSON>, it was the Radicals against the <ORGANIZATION> Peronists </ORGANIZATION>,'' losing candidate <PERSON> Italo </PERSON> <PERSON> Argentino </PERSON> <PERSON> Luder </PERSON> said in an interview, referring to <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> swamped <PERSON> Luder </PERSON>, 52 percent to 40 in the balloting for president in post-military <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. `` Now, it is totally different,'' the 71-year-old <PERSON> Luder </PERSON> said. `` The economy is the biggest theme _ inflation, foreign debt, growth, employment, purchasing power ... -LRB- and -RRB- the Radicals have totally failed in government.'' Pollster <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mora </PERSON> y <PERSON> Araujo </PERSON>'s surveys consistently give <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> twice as big a share of the vote as <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON>, though he notes that undecideds have crept up to 35 percent. `` You ca n't say -LRB- <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s -RRB- victory is beyond doubt, but he's definitely ahead,'' the pollster said <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> founded the party following his victory in the elections of 1946, the most honest and widely attended in two decades. An army colonel at the time, <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> later was promoted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to general. With his wildly popular and politically astute wife <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> at his side and sometimes acting on her own, <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> won the support of workers disenfranchised by previous conservative governments. <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> industrialized an agricultural economy based on grain and beef, nationalized industries, promoted such legislation as collective bargaining and pensions, vastly extended public education and health services, and gave women the right to vote. <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> established a dictatorship that remained popular so long as <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> _ </PERSON> <PERSON> Evita </PERSON>, as she was affectionately known _ was around. Popular support began to diminish after her death of cancer in 1952 and with the economy in trouble in 1955 the military overthrew <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> and sent him into exile in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. He made a triumphal return in 1971 and was elected president again in 1973, with his new wife, <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON>, as his vice president. She took the presidency upon <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>'s death in 1974 only to be ousted by the military two years later. While the <ORGANIZATION> Perons </ORGANIZATION> themselves have had their ups and downs, the party has generally maintained its base of organized labor and the poor. The 4-million-member General Workers Confederation, the chief labor union, `` was born, is and will always be Peronist,'' the 53-year-old <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> told a recent rally. But party leaders now are trying to appeal to the middle class, which they see as key to the 50 percent of the vote required by Argentine law to win the election outright and avoid a runoff in the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Luder </PERSON>, an attorney who is one of <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s advisers, says appealing to the middle class is a natural move. `` Peronism created this country as we know it today,'' he said. `` The sons and grandsons of the workers of 1946 today are businessmen, teachers, professionals.'' Argentines in those stations, however, tend to support the <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> or the conservative Union of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Alsogaray </PERSON>, a former economy minister and former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador. Today's Peronists are finding their overtures frustrated by the party's image of violence, demagoguery and administrative incompetence, a public perception <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> calls his party's `` black legend.'' Even triple-digit inflation, rising unemployment, stagnant growth and three military insurrections under President <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> can not shake the recollections of better-off Argentines that some of the country's economic and political low points occurred under <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> governments. <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> squandered huge gold reserves built up during World War II, crowded out private business by expanding the state's role in the economy, made public employment conditional on party membership, tolerated corruption and thuggery against his opponents, closed down newspapers, antagonized the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. In the final months before <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> was ousted by the military in 1976, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> was torn by murderous street violence, out-of-control inflation and paralyzing strikes. `` Peronist governments have never understood economics,'' said <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Balassoni </PERSON>, a medical products importer. `` It's very possible he -LRB- <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> -RRB- would return control to the unions, so the unions would govern, not the government.'' A well-dressed, middle-aged woman at a rally for <PERSON> Alsogaray </PERSON> in a downtown sports stadium said, `` If <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> wins, the country will slide backwards, despite his best intentions. ... I favor shrinking the size of the state, selling state companies. The Peronists would never sell state companies.'' National elections set for May 14 may hang in the balance of opinions like theirs. Votes in the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> are tied to the popular ballot. If <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> fails to win at least 50 percent, <PERSON> Alsogaray </PERSON> could determine the election by throwing his support to <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON>. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> at times seems to hurt his own cause by endorsing ideas that appear contradictory and are never fully explained. Although <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> is a country notorious for tax evasion, <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> has said he would curtail the fiscal deficit not by cutting back state employment or selling off money-losing state enterprises, but by cutting tax rates in the hope that would spur compliance and generate additional revenue. Under his program, workers would receive big wage increases, but he has not fully explained where the money would come from. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s allies do n't always help. While he tries to project an image of moderation and statesmanship, Mrs. <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> in November dredged up unhappy memories by endorsing an amnesty for the former military chiefs who directed the so-called `` dirty war'' against subversives and the leftist Montonero urban guerrillas in the 1970s. At least 8,900 Argentines were arrested and `` disappeared'' during that campaign. Forced to take a position on that sensitive issue, <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> said he opposed an amnesty. In another case, the leader of a leftist <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> splinter group, <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Unamuno </PERSON>, publicly stated that <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> would pardon <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Firmenich </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Montonero </LOCATION> leader who is in prison for murder, extortion and kidnapping. An angry <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> denied he planned any such pardon and suspended Unamuno from the party. The Radicals have seized upon such rifts and gaffes to fan passions and fears that are never far from the surface in this politically polarized country. `` Violence is part of their history,'' said <PERSON> Angeloz </PERSON>'s press secretary, <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> still has violent elements in its structure.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs Dec. 26</NOTE>
