<FIRST>a i AM-TortureDoctors Adv29   12-20 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Torture Doctors, Adv 29,0967</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Adv for Release Thur AMs Dec. 29 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Treatment Center Says Doctors Present at Torturings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUNILLA FARINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Patients at <PERSON> Inge </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> <PERSON> Genefke </PERSON>'s clinic for torture victims say their injuries often were inflicted in the presence of doctors, nurses or psychologists _ people trained to heal. The Danish physician said it has become clear during six years of treating battered refugees and studying torture cases that medical personnel nearly always were involved, even if only giving tacit assent. In a well-documented case in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, a prison psychologist advised torturers on how to break victims. Studies by the clinic indicate up to 25,000 people in the medical profession are involved. `` Torture could not take place to the extent it does today if doctors were not implicated,'' the doctor said. `` These doctors should be thrown out of medical organizations, and not only in their own country.'' Dr. <PERSON> Genefke </PERSON> is director of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Torture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victims </ORGANIZATION>. It treats victims, publishes educational material, trains doctors and psychologists in the care of victims and conducts courses for police and others who deal with refugees. It is private and independent, financed by the government and private donations. Her study of torture started 15 years ago, when Dr. <PERSON> Genefke </PERSON> was in a group of physicians asked by the <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> group </ORGANIZATION> to examine victims for evidence of torture. She opened the center in 1982 in a wing of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION> and has helped establish similar facilities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and elsewhere. The <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION> clinic has a staff of 30 doctors, psychologists and others who treat 70-100 victims and families every year. The 1988 Right Livelihood Award was given to Dr. <PERSON> Genefke </PERSON>. <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakob </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Uexkull </PERSON> established the prize in 1980 for humanitarian work. Estimates by the center indicate 30 percent of the approximately 24,000 people given asylum in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> have been exposed to torture. `` We used to believe that medical personnel participating in torture was a rare phenomenon, but now we know that almost all torture victims have been in contact with them in the actual torture process,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Vesti </PERSON>, a staff psychiatrist. `` Today we know the purpose of torture is not to get information, but to destroy the personality and spread terror to control the population.'' In 1986, the center broadened its scope to include research and documentation on torture, in cooperation with doctors in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. An international committee has been formed to expose illegal practices and revoke licenses of doctors involved with torture. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> has estimated torture is practiced in at least 90 countries. `` In <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, the medical associations have been extremely brave and courageous,'' Dr. <PERSON> Genefke </PERSON> said. Several hundred military doctors are believed involved in torture in each of those countries, the center has reported. Dr. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON>, former director of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s medical association, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> four doctors had been expelled and two suspended from membership. `` They are a really astounding example of how national medical associations can deal with this issue,'' <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Stover </PERSON> of the American Association for the Advancement of Science said in a telephone interview. `` Not only have they disciplined physicians while the <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> government is in power, they have adopted a set of guidelines for physicians.'' <PERSON> Stover </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s was a unique case of a medical association acting against doctors involved in torture while a military government remained in power. In <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, where democracy was restored in 1985, the ethics board of the physicians' union imposed sanctions on four doctors, including <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Saiz </PERSON>, found to have issued a death certificate in 1984 that concealed evidence of torture. All four continue practicing medicine in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, however. About 200 doctors have given depositions about their activities under the military dictatorship that began in 1973, but action has been taken only against <PERSON> Saiz </PERSON> and the other three. In <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> last March, the <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> revoked the license of <PERSON> Amilcar </PERSON> <PERSON> Lobo </PERSON>, an army doctor who attended torture sessions in 1970-1974. Brazilian press reports say <PERSON> Lobo </PERSON> has implicated other doctors but no formal charges have resulted. <PERSON> Emilie </PERSON> <PERSON> Trautmann </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Turkish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> was investigating charges in that country. Dr. <PERSON> Genefke </PERSON> said the involvement of medical people in torture can take many forms: `` For example, a doctor can examine a prisoner and conclude that he or she has a weak heart and should not have electrical torture, because they are not supposed to die.'' She also said psychological torture, often involving threats, can be worse than physical punishment. Her center has done extensive research on torture methods in order to develop the most effective medical and psychological care for victims. Most are treated as outpatients. Treatment at the center combines physiotherapy, psychotheraphy and social counseling. It usually lasts 10 to 12 months. The clinic decor is cheerful and the atmosphere friendly. Beige and yellow furniture and flowered textiles are used to reduce the resemblance to a medical institution. Patients report such tortures as hanging by hands or elbows, sometimes for days; electric shocks; beatings, amd holding the head under filthy water. Long afterward, patients often have such symptoms as sexual disturbance, hallucinations, fear, confusion, nightmares and loss of self-confidence and self-respect, <PERSON> Vesti </PERSON> said. As Dr. <PERSON> Genefke </PERSON> explained it: `` There is so much fear, anger, aggressions, shame and guilt that has to be expressed, and it is very, very difficult. We do n't call our patients torture victims, we call them torture survivors.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thur AMs Dec. 27</NOTE>
