<FIRST>s i BC-WorldSymposium Adv01-3Takes   12-20 1170</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-World Symposium, Adv 01-3 Takes,1200</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Jan. 1, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WORLD SYMPOSIUM '89 _ What Lies Ahead Abroad for George Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, an accompanying story is BC-Symposium-Neighbors, b0540</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Almost from the minute he takes the presidential oath Jan. 20, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will face a raft of fast-developing foreign policy issues in a world that has changed radically from the one <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> found eight years before. Most immediately pressing, perhaps, is the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, where the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could be on the verge of its first major involvement in a peace effort since <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s shuttle diplomacy of the 1970s. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s changing <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and more U.S.-Soviet arms agreements also are likely items on the agenda for the early days of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> presidency. Then there is <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and its new contacts with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where the East is at a crossroads, and the West looks with less trepidation toward the Soviet bloc; <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, with its debt and economic stagnation; <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where South African apartheid remains a troublesome and delicate issue for the White House; and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, where burgeoning economies still pour goods into Main Street, U.S.A. Even the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, the place people dream of for tranquil escape, has become a piece in the world chess game. Each year at this time, The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> asks its correspondents in strategic areas of the world to look ahead to what Americans can expect abroad in the new year. For 1989, they were asked to look ahead to what President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> can expect in his first year in office. These are their reports:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MIDDLE EAST</HEAD>
<HEAD>BY ED BLANCHE</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> inherits a rapidly changing climate in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, where a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> holds the seeds of a possible breakthrough in settling the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's decision Dec. 14 to talk to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> after its chairman, <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, said the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> recognized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist and renounced terrorism, will give <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the opportunity to make a significant impact on the long-stalled peace process. Whatever the outcome of the U.S.-PLO dialogue, it will put pressure on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, appalled at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision, to negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> on the creation of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state declared in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s Parliament-in-exile. With <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> increasingly isolated, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could be in a position to encourage Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> to be more flexible. But there will likely be hard bargaining amid <PERSON> Arab </PERSON>, Soviet and European pressure for an international peace conference attended by the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will also find new possibilities for resuming relations with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> under the Islamic republic's developing open-door policy of improving its ties with the rest of the world, ending nine years of political isolation. That could improve the prospects of freeing Western hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Most of the 16 foreigners, including nine Americans, are held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOVIET UNION</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In less than four years, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has painted over the image of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as a boastful, missile-wielding totalitarian state with a portrait of a hopeful giant struggling to pull itself up by the bootstraps and join the community of peaceful nations. But the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> still has those missiles, and if President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is to continue a period of easing world tensions, he must find some way to break the deadlock that prevented his predecessor from signing an agreement with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to slash strategic arsenals in half. The initial roadblock remains President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s `` Star Wars'' program to develop a space-based defense against missile attack. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> insists such a program only opens a new, dangerous arena for the arms race and makes reductions in offensive weapons impossible. Beyond that lie unresolved questions about how the two sides can fairly balance reductions in their inherently different land, sea and air weapons systems. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is busy not only trying to restructure the economy and way of thinking in his own country, but he also is trying to break down East-West barriers and develop new trade relationships throughout the world. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has moved more slowly than some nations in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to encourage an end to Soviet isolation and support development of a potentially powerful new Soviet market. Some Westerners have suggested the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s efforts to improve relations, particularly with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, could weaken <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ties to its <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> partners as <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> works to build what he calls a `` common European home.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EASTERN EUROPE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> faces a delicate balancing act between Communist authorities opening up to reform and the increasingly vocal and active independent groups who want the West to insist on more human rights. As in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, Communist governments in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> are realizing they must open up to economic and perhaps political reform in order to modernize outmoded industry and keep consumer demands satisfied. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, for the time being, have rejected any need for the change their allies have embraced with varying degrees of enthusiasm. But new laws allowing more private and foreign investment in East bloc economies will not boost output unless the West agrees to make large loans and import or sell its advanced technology. Some West European leaders have talked of a kind of `` Marshall Plan'' to help out <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where massive investment would be needed to provide modern housing and industry and clean up the heavily polluted environment. But independent groups encouraged by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are also placing increasing demands for genuine democracy. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade with Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> traditionally has been small. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will have a voice in determining the stand of allies like <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, with significant business activities in the East, as they try to juggle the demands of Communists for more money and activists for a firm stand on human rights.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WESTERN EUROPE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will find a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> preoccupied with contentious arms control talks, efforts to unify its market and a continuing flirtation with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will likely meet in the spring with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> leaders at a summit of the 16-nation <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> to discuss pressing issues. By that time, the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies may well have begun negotiations _ called the <ORGANIZATION> Conventional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stability </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Talks </ORGANIZATION> _ with the seven <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> nations on reducing conventional arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The allies recently unveiled their joint position, which calls for substantial reductions in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's tanks, artillery and other forces, surpassing the unilateral cuts promised by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in a surprise announcement at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in early December. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> contends the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact holds a massive superiority in such weapons.
