<HEAD>NEIGHBOR CANADA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> will be looking for reassurance from President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that it is trusted as an ally and valued as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' No. 1 trading partner. A bruising campaign that gave Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> his second consecutive majority government put the spotlight on Canadian concerns that the country is taken for granted, ignored or overshadowed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The victory for <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> cleared the way for the free trade agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to proceed, but it is a long-term pact that will be phased in over 10 years. Canadians will be looking for some signs that their willingness to cooperate with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> can produce some tangible results in an easing of the trade squabbles still likely to occur in aspects uncovered by the agreement. And, with economic growth expected to slow down in both countries, great attention will be paid here to any plant closings attributed to the new trade pact. In other issues, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> will be looking to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to take promised steps to cut down sulphur dioxide emissions blamed in large part for producing the acid rain that devastates Canadian aquatic life in sensitive lakes and streams. The private Canadian Coalition on Acid Rain found <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s stand on acid rain an improvement over the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's record but `` weaker and vaguer'' than <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEIGHBOR MEXICO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> face as many problems as ever, but under the presidencies of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> their historically prickly relationship will probably improve. Prime among problems in the coming months will be <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s foreign debt, now $ 102 billion <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> says the $ 13 billion annual payments should be reduced because they are n't leaving enough money for economic growth. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, inaugurated Dec. 1, is expected to tell bankers in 1989 that stifling growth is counterproductive in the long run. Renewing growth is vital for <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, because the average Mexican's standard of living has suffered badly during years of austerity. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> won a disputed election and better conditions would strengthen his mandate. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has given <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> a sympathetic ear, and the two appeared to hit it off when they met in November. A recent $ 3.5 billion <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> loan offer was seen as a vote of confidence. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> is a hard-nosed negotiator, but he is unlikely to let pride get in the way of practical solutions. Other issues: _ Trade: <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> fears protectionist sentiment will cut access to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets, restricting growth opportunities A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> recession would also hurt <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> if exports went down. _ Migration: <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> resents the way migrants looking for jobs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are treated, since they fill an apparent need <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> argues that growth is a key here too, because more jobs in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> would reduce migration. _ Drugs: <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has promised a harder fight against drug trafficking, but expects the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to crack down on demand _ <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>: Mexicans are hopeful the new administration will focus less on an anti-communist crusade in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, which was very unpopular here
