<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices began the week on a mixed note, with wholesale unleaded gasoline gaining more ground but the rest of the market retreating sharply. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the January contract for unleaded gasoline settled at 45.42 cents a gallon Monday, up 0.29 cent from the close Friday, when it rose 1.48 cents. Other contract months declined. Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Monday, January wholesale home heating oil fell 1.27 cents to 50.75 cents a gallon, after jumping 1.08 cents Friday. The January contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, settled at $ 16.31 a barrel, down 41 cents from Friday. It rose 37 cents in the previous session. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, a senior energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, attributed Monday's price movements largely to technical factors. `` I think WTI and heating oil were a bit overbought ... and besides we're due for some warmer weather'' in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, thereby lessening the demand for heating oil, he said.
