<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>3-Month T-Bills Reach 8.14 Percent in Latest Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities rose in the government's latest auction to the highest level in more than 3 -LCB- years. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7.2 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 8.14 percent on Monday, up from 7.98 percent last week. Another $ 7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 8.29 percent, up from 8.21 percent last week. The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 8.18 percent on April 1, 1985 and six-month bills averaged 8.56 on April 8, 1985. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 8.43 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,794.20 and and 8.77 percent for six-month bills selling for $ 9,580.90. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the average yild for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 9.10 percent last week after averaging 8.89 percent the week before.
