<HEAD>Recap of Major Events in Pillsbury Takeover Struggle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pillsbury Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 _ Oct 4, 1988: Grand Metropolitan PLC, a British distilling, gambling and food giant, makes a surprise $ 60-a-share, $ 5.23 billion offer for <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the Minneapolis-based food and restaurant chain subjected to repeated takeover rumors in preceding months because of its depressed stock price. The offer is 53 percent more than <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s closing stock price of Oct. 3. _ Oct 6: <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> tells the company's 100,000 employees the <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Met </ORGANIZATION> offer is illegal and he refuses to meet with the suitor Besides asserting its `` poison pill'' shareholder-rights anti-takeover bylaw, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> plans a complex defense that reportedly includes an effort to overturn Grand Met's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> liquor-distribution licenses It also creates an ad depicting the famed <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> `` doughboy'' strutting boxing gloves. _ Oct 17: <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> board formally declares the Grand Met order inadequate and orders advisers to explore alternatives. _ Nov 7: Faced with increased pressure to capitulate by dissident shareholders, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> proposes spinoff of Burger King fast-food subsidiary as part of defensive restructuring to thwart Grand Met, but the proposal is widely criticized as a feeble effort to remain independent. Meanwhile, Grand Met says nearly 75 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s shares have been tendered, but acquisition of the company is delayed by legal haggling over <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s poison pill defense. _ Nov 13: Reports surface that <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> may attempt a so-called `` Pac-Man'' defense by acquiring Grand Met, which is twice <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s size. Grand Met's management expresses concern about it, but <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> declines comment. _ Nov 20: <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> board delays spinoff of Burger King in response to opposition from the chain's 1,400 franchises. _ Nov 30: <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> suggests it would be willing to meet with Grand Met if a higher offer emerged. _ Dec 9-11: Weekend bargaining results in a sweetened Grand Met offer of $ 63, but <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> balks at an agreement. _ Dec 16: A <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> judge invalidates <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s poison pill defense and further postpones Burger King spinoff. A separate ruling by a <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> judge also blocks the Burger King spinoff. Hours later, both sides agree to a $ 66-a-share takeover worth $ 5.68 billion. _ Dec 18: <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> board formally announces approval of the takeover.
