<FIRST>r f PM-StockDisputes     12-20 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stock Disputes,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Court Throws Out State Stock Arbitration Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has thrown out controversial first-in-the-nation state regulations, inspired by the 1987 stock market crash, that allowed stock traders to sue brokers more easily in financial disputes. In a 36-page ruling issued Monday, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> threw out regulations promulgated in September by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>. The regulations, set to take effect Jan., prevented stockbrokers from requiring customers to agree to arbitration in stock disputes instead of lawsuits. A top aide to <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said the state likely would appeal the ruling. A coalition of brokers sued the state in September and <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> heard the case two weeks ago. In his ruling he said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 upheld the use of pre-dispute arbitration clauses to govern resolution of controversies between brokers and their customers. Typically, the agreements state that in the event of a dispute, the customer and the broker would go into arbitration before a mutually acceptable party _ the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, for example _ rather than take the case to court. <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> ruled in favor of the brokers who argued that arbitration is a quicker, cheaper way of settling disputes and that <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> had improperly usurped federal authority in regulating securities trading. `` On the evidence before me, it appears that court litigation affords customers the opportunity to pay more in legal costs to get less in recovery,'' <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> wrote. `` To the degree that arbitration constitutes a more economical form of dispute resolution, it may be anticipated that regulations which discourage arbitration will have the effect of raising commission rates.'' The regulations, <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> said, `` single out arbitration agreements for more demanding standards than are imposed by the general law of contract in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> said the state regulations would increase the federal caseload at a time when the court system is already overburdened. `` My clients are delighted that the court agreed with our position that these regulations were invalid,'' said attorney <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rath </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> law firm <ORGANIZATION> Bingham </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rath </PERSON> represents the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and 10 brokerage firms, including <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brokerage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Deputy Secretary of State <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Meehan </PERSON> said officials in <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>'s securities division still were reviewing the ruling Monday evening but he said, `` in all likelihood we will request the attorney general to appeal the decision. <PERSON> Meehan </PERSON> said the regulations stemmed from a flood of complaints following the stockmarket crash of October 1987 when thousands of customers alleged that their urgent stock transactions were misplaced or mishandled. In the disputes that followed, <PERSON> Meehan </PERSON> said, stock customers found to their surprise that they had signed away their right to sue. The state regulations would have required brokers to fully disclose the terms of their arbitration agreements and give customers the option of maintaining their right to sue in court. `` Our beef is n't necessarily with the arbitration process,'' <PERSON> Meehan </PERSON> said. `` Our concern is with investors signing away their rights unknowingly.'' <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON> said full disclosure is desirable but is not adequately defined in the state regulations.
</TEXT>
