<HEAD>Sotheby's Reports 27.5 Percent Increase in Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s, the international auction house, reported a 27.5 percent increase in auction sales during 1988, highlighted by the sale of collections belonging to <PERSON> Elton </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> and paintings by <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON>. Worldwide sales totaled $ 1.814 billion in 1988, compared with $ 1.423 billion last year and more than triple the 1984 figure of $ 586 million, said a statement released Monday by the 244-year-old auction house. The statement quoted <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ainslie </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, as saying that while `` extraordinary prices'' were being reached at the top end of the market, the middle and low ranges also were doing well, with about 190,000 lots valued at under 10,000 dollars sold in 1988. The statement did not mention <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s annual profit. <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s noted the art collection belonging to <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, the late American pop artist, sold for around $ 25.3 million, and British singer <PERSON> Elton </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s sold for $ 8.7 million. `` False Start'' by <PERSON> Johns </PERSON>, the American artist, fetched $ 17.05 million, a record for a work by a living artist and for any contemporary work sold at auction, the Sotheby's statement said. <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>'s `` La Cage d'Oiseaux'' went for $ 15.4 million, it said. Other notable sales were the original manuscript of <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>'s novel `` The Trial,'' which brought nearly $ 2 million, four times the previous record for a modern literary manuscript, it said A console table made for <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoinette </PERSON> sold for nearly $ 3 million, and a Cycladic marble head of a goddess fetched $ 2.09 million, a record for a classical antiquity. The typescript of <LOCATION> Orson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Welles </LOCATION>' 1938 radio broadcast of `` The War of the Worlds'' was sold for $ 143,000 and the piano that featured in the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> scene from the movie `` Casablanca'' went for $ 154,000, it said. <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s also said that in 1988 it staged the first international auction in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and was the first Western auction house to hold a sale in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
