<HEAD>Random Drug Testing Barred for 3 Million Truckers, Bus Drivers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7th graf to add no comment from Transportation
Department officials and to clarify when testing was to begin. Picks
up in 6th graf, `Jeffrey King ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge blocked a federal plan to require random drug testing of 3 million interstate drivers nationwide but did allow pre-employment and post-accident testing. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> <PERSON> Patel </PERSON> issued a temporary restraining order Monday against random drug testing of truckers and interstate bus drivers. She told government lawyers she wanted to review how widespread substance abuse is in the trucking industry before a future hearing. The material published in the Federal Register in support of testing amounted to nothing more than `` a well-taken diatribe against drug abuse in American society,'' <PERSON> Patel </PERSON>. The program was to start Wednesday, but the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> did not require companies to conduct any actual testing until next December, according to department spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON>. More than 1 million other private employees in the rail, airline and maritime industries are scheduled to begin random testing. The order expires Dec. 30, when <PERSON> Patel </PERSON> is scheduled to hear arguments on a longer-lasting injunction against all testing programs affecting truckers and interstate bus drivers. Marks declined to comment on <PERSON> Patel </PERSON>'s ruling, saying the government would present its side on Dec. 30. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, lawyer for the <ORGANIZATION> Owner-Operator </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drivers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, which challenged the testing program, said drug abuse among truck drivers `` is probably below the national average.'' `` There's no basis to think there's a severe problem,'' King told reporters. He said random drug testing would sacrifice `` the rights of millions of truck drivers ... in hopes of catching a few.'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said his organization, which has 9,000 members, sued on behalf of all 300,000 independent owners of heavy-duty trucks and small truck fleets. He said <PERSON> Patel </PERSON>'s order applies to all interstate truck and bus drivers, but not to inter-city bus drivers, who have separate drug testing regulations. <PERSON> King </PERSON> said he hoped to reach agreement with government lawyers on an extension of the ban on random drug testing before the temporary restraining order expires. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> testing program was announced Nov. 14. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said at the time that transportation employees were no more immune from drug abuse than the rest of society, listing a series of accidents and other evidence.
