<HEAD>EEC Asks GATT Council For Support In Hormones Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday called for a <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> ruling in the dispute over the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> ban on hormone-treated meat which is to take effect Jan. 1 and threatens to trigger a trade war with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> immediately opposed the request, saying the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> sought an `` instantanous legal finding'' that had no basis under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> representative, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON>, told the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> that the threatened <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retaliatory measures, a 100 percent punitive duty on a range of products, were a `` further affront against the multilateral trade system'' set up by the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>. He said the case had wide ramifications and urged the council to rule on the legal issues involved and decide on remedies. A top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade negotiator, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON>, said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> ban amounted to a `` unilateral decision to simply prohibit $ 120 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports per year.'' He said it was a `` wholesale disruption of traditional trade flows'' on alleged grounds of health but that the measure was not backed up by scientific evidence. <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> had repeatedly rejected proposals to have the case examined by an impartial scientific body. He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> remained willing to pursue the matter under any appropriate <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> process as long as the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> deferred the ban. <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> was aware that there were different views on the use of growth hormones in meat but that it had to `` listen to its consumers'' who did not want such meat. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> supported the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, saying that it considered the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> approach excessive. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, the Canadian representative, said in the brief debate that growth hormones were proven to be safe if used properly. There was no decision on the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> request and the matter was expected to come up again at the next <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> session in February. In other business, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> formally demanded that a <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> panel be set up to rule in its dispute with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over punitive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> duties imposed in response to an alleged lack of Brazilian patent protection for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pharmaceutical products. <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> ambassador <PERSON> Rubens </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricupero </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retaliation was in clear violation of <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> rules and in breach of commitments not to impose new unilateral trade restrictions during the current <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> round of world trade liberalization talks. <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON> said there had been no alternative left to defending legitimate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests but that the measures would be lifted as soon as <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> acts upon the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request to ensure full patent proection. The measures cover $ 39 million worth of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s trade with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, an amount which <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON> said reflects the damage suffered by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pharmaceutical industry. Twenty-eight countries backed <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s position, including the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, which said also that the case argued for action on patents in the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> round talks. As the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> opposed the Brazilian request up a panel, the council did not take a decision but was expected to discuss the case again at its February session.
