<NOTE>For Release AMs Wednesday Dec. 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>`To Succeed You Must Eat, Sleep and Dream Your Goals'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>, 74, recently stepped up the pace. Rather than growing his business at just 15 percent a year, which would double volume in five years, he publicly announced a goal of 17.5 percent a year. At that rate <ORGANIZATION> Carlson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>, a personally owned 75-company conglomerate based in <LOCATION> Minnetonka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, would double its annual volume to $ 9 billion in 1992. Already, it is as large as some Fortune 100 companies. Unlike such companies, however, <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> remains entrepreneurial, constantly setting sales goals, publicly stating them so that there is no retreat, then setting new goals. It has never missed a five-year sales goal. <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> LeRoy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> was selling soap to grocery stores in 1938 when he founded <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stamp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Constantly diversifying into other businesses, restlessly setting goals, he pushed company sales to $ 1 billion in 1978. Averaged out over the 40 years, that growth came to 33 percent a year compounded. The company was huge now, and growth of that sort does n't come as easily as in the smaller days. For one thing, you have to seek public funds. So, said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>, in 1978 he thought it best to `` settle'' for 15 percent a year for the next five years. In 1982 sales reached $ 2 billion. Another 15 percent five-year plan began. In 1987 the company reached $ 4 billion. Ever the entrepreneur, <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> then looked at his cash flow and decided there was enough money coming in to step up the pace to 17.5 percent. That's the goal each year through 1992. There's no resting at <ORGANIZATION> Carlson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos </ORGANIZATION>. The conglomerate now has four major divisions: hospitality, incentives, travel and promotion. Among the companies are the highly rated Radisson hotel chain, TGI Friday's restaurants, <ORGANIZATION> Ask </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mr. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the oldest and largest in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> E.F. </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>'s incentive travel, <ORGANIZATION> Carlson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Learning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION> It is forever in transition, continually evolving. In its evolution the company follows no rigid plan, says <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>. `` I hire top people and they grow the company,'' he says. `` We're pulled ahead by big horses.'' Enthusiasm, imagination, innovation and motivation are important elements in <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>'s type of management, and goal-setting is basic to all of them. It began with little self-reminders in <PERSON> Curt </PERSON>'s wallet Now it's institutionalized. `` To succeed you must eat, sleep and dream your goals and quotas,'' he says. `` It's a fact, an absolute fact: You will never make as much progress without targets as you will with goal setting.'' Nevertheless, he calls himself cautious. He seeks to grow in `` bite sizes; I do n't shoot the wad.'' That way, if things do n't turn out as expected, `` you get a little blip in the earnings that can be corrected. Incentives spur achievement, and <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> officers who achieve are given such things as first-class, 17-day tours of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. Throughout the year spouses are kept informed of how well their mates are doing. Not wanting to be left out, they spur their mates to higher achievement. The company remains the very same as it was 50 years ago in at least one respect: it is sales driven. `` You build as fast as you can,'' said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> the other day. `` As soon as a salesman is making his pay you put on another.'' Every month <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> examines the income statement and balance sheet for each of the 75 companies. He watches the bottom line, the pursuit of goals. Should he suspect problems, he asks for backup information and explanations. So successful are the <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> management techniques that some of his people would set _ and probably reach _ even higher goals. But, says <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>, `` you can only grow as fast as the money comes in.'' To open a new Friday's, for example, might take $ 2 million. `` I can not open 40 of them without taking money away from others.'' In a sense, therefore, the big growth goals are probably compromises. Perhaps its just as well because the goals are always publicly stated. As a consequence, they are avidly watched by the media. Fail to achieve a goal and everyone in town will know about it. `` You burn your bridges behind you,'' said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> the magic motivator. `` We give a figure and we had better make it, because everyone is watching.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday Dec. 20</NOTE>
