<SECOND>AM-Bush-Deficit, 1st Ld-Writethru,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Appoints Laxalt, Ashley to Deficit Commission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with appointments, Bush quotes</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, emphasizing his opposition to tax increases, appointed Republican <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Laxalt </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> on Tuesday to a national commission struggling to find a formula for reducing the federal budget deficit. `` I intend to hold the line on taxes,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` There are a lot of people around saying I ca n't do that.'' <PERSON> Laxalt </PERSON>, onetime governor of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, served two terms in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> before joining a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> law firm. <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, a longtime personal friend of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s, spent 26 years in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> and was a top-ranking member of the <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He now is president of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION>, a lobbying group which represents the country's largest banks. The appointments put the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> at its full strength of 14 people. The panel was created last year after the stock market's 508-point plunge. Some business leaders said <PERSON> Laxalt </PERSON>'s appointment diminished the possibility that the commission would recommend tax increases to cut the deficit. `` Laxalt is the type of guy who has read <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s lips, and from everything I know about him he would be against taxes and would want to look on the spending side for deficit reductions,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahn </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` He has been a good fiscal conservative.'' Tempering skepticism that he voiced earlier, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` Some have suggested I am something less than enthralled with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. That's not right.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who takes office on Jan. 20, made that comment in a meeting with about 30 business leaders who pledged their support for a program of reducing the deficit by cutting spending rather than raising taxes. He issued a written statement later announcing the appointment of <LOCATION> Laxalt </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>. He noted that his announcement came only one day after the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> ratified the Nov. 8 vote electing him president. `` The swiftness with which I am making these appointments underscores the importance I place on the need to reduce the federal budget deficit,'' he said. `` I believe that the experience these two public servants will bring to the panel will add to the quality of its deliberations,'' he said. At the beginning of the meeting with the business leaders, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called the deficit a tough problem. `` I'll just do my level best to send signals to the international markets that we're serious, that we're projecting it downward firmly, and I really believe that once that happens the adverse psychology that is forcing interest rates up beyond where in my view they ought to be will turn around,'' he said. `` I think once world markets think that we're definitively on a track without exception to have the deficit obliterated in whatever number of years it is, that in itself _ a bipartisan answer _ that in itself will be enormously beneficial to world markets,'' he said. In the past, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has appeared suspicious of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, warning that it might try to promote a tax-increase plan to cut the deficit. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Tuesday he was looking forward to hearing from the group and listening to its suggestions. `` There are some very good people on there, Democrats and Republicans. They're serious, serious people. ... So I'm not looking for a battle with the them and there wo n't be one because they've been most cooperative since the election in terms of wanting to at least have from our key economic appointees their views.''
</TEXT>
