<FIRST>u f AM-Inflation-Markets Bjt   12-20 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inflation-Markets, Bjt,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inflation Report Boosts Financial Markets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Economy Rdp</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An encouraging report on inflation Tuesday added a spark of life to some financial markets and eased concerns about higher interest rates, but most analysts remained wary about the economy's direction. The dollar rallied against most major currencies in foreign exchange trading here and abroad, while bond prices headed sharply higher. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year issue rose nearly $ 10 per $ 1,000 face amount, while its yield, which moves inversely to price, fell below 9 percent for the first time in a week. On Wall Street, however, stocks declined. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which shot up around 14 points at the opening, closed down 6.61 to 2,166.07. Economists said the markets were encouraged by a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report that showed inflation on the consumer level slowed in November to an annual rate of just 3 percent. A drop in clothing prices and stabilized prices for food contributed to the decline, the department said. With only December left, another month similar to November could enable the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to finish its last year in office meeting its inflation target of 4.3 percent for 1988, down slightly from 1987's 4.4 percent level. Also easing inflation worries was a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report that the gross national product _ the broadest measure of economic health _ expanded at a moderate annual rate of 2.5 percent in the third quarter due to the summer drought. For the same period, the department reported that after-tax corporate profits rose 3.9 percent, down from a robust 8.9 percent increase the previous quarter. `` Low inflation is good for all the markets. It means the -LRB- economic -RRB- recovery was sustainable and long-lived,'' said <PERSON> Maury </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. It eases the pressure on interest rates, which have risen sharply in recent weeks partly on inflationary fears. Inflation is considered the nemesis of the financial markets, particularly the credit markets, because it erodes the value of fixed-income securities, sending yields higher to compensate for the loss. That depresses the stock market, which competes for investor money. And it often hurts the dollar because as prices of stocks and bonds slip, foreigners become less willing to exchange their currencies for dollars to buy those <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> securities. Talk around Wall Street lately had centered around whether the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will raise its discount rate, a key short-term rate, to prevent the economy from overheating and inflation from heading up. The discount rate is the interest the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> charges on loans to member banks and savings institutions, and it's considered the most direct vehicle for the central bank to make its credit policies known. Most economists had predicted the rate would be raised 0.5 percentage point to 7 percent. However, Tuesday's inflation and GNP reports put some of those discussions to rest, at least temporarily. `` Some people who jumped on the interest-rates-going-up, fed-tightening bandwagon found out they were going on it prematurely,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief financial economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. International `` That's what the markets are telling you.'' <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> A. Stone, a senior economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, admits she was part of that majority group. `` We had expected that given the strength in some of the other economic numbers lately that we'd see the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> raising the discount rate pretty soon,'' she said. `` Well this -LRB- economic data -RRB- suggests that they may not have to do that right away, although there's still a good possibility after the first of the year that we'd see that happen.'' `` There are some people that are ... expecting a rise in the discount rate and the -LRB- bank's -RRB- prime rate before year's end,'' added <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON>, a money market economist for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said that while the latest reports point to less inflation and slightly slower economic growth, `` a laundry list'' of other factors point in another direction `` The dollar remains weak overall, -LRB- business -RRB- capacity use rates are high and rising, and we have a very low unemployment rate,'' he said. `` Oil prices are also rising.''
</TEXT>
