<HEAD>St. Lawrence Seaway Boosts Some Tolls, Exempts Humanitarian Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most tolls on the St. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Seaway </PERSON> will increase by 4.5 percent in each of the next two years, officials of the binational waterway said Tuesday. The higher tolls being levied in 1989 and 1990 are needed to help the system keep pace with inflation, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Seaway Administrator <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Emery </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Seaway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>. However, tolls for humanitarian-aid shipments will be eliminated and lumber shipments will be reclassified as bulk cargo and therefore have a lower toll, officials said. These moves are intended to spur increased movement of those two cargos. The combined toll for general cargo on the seaway in 1989 is $ 2.86 per metric ton, while the rate for bulk cargo is $ 1.33 per ton. To be qualify for the lower rate, the lumber must be timber or logs, sawed or split and rough or dressed into various sizes for use as beams, joists, rafters, studs, boards of planks. `` There is an abundance of forest land and wood product industries in the western Great Lakes region,'' <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> said. `` The seaway is a natural transportation route for this virtually untapped market.'' However, he said the seaway handled only 9,400 metric tons of lumber shipments in 1987, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Canadian agencies are hoping for a significant increase in the amount of lumber shipped through the system.
