<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose Tuesday, strengthened by yearend corporate demand, speculation of higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates and a sharp jump in oil prices. Gold prices fell marginally in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> after mostly rising abroad. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted bullion at $ 413.90 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $ 414 late Monday. Currency strategists attributed the dollar's rise largely to orders for the currency from U.S.-based multinationals preparing to repatriate 1988 earnings. `` There is always good corporate demand for dollars in the last couple of weeks of the year,'' said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Yannalfo </PERSON>, senior foreign exchange trader at <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> commodities futures firm. Others said persistent speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would tighten interest rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> raised demand for dollars. Higher interest rates make dollar-denominated holdings worth more. In addition, an oil price hike in the energy markets supported the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency, since most oil contracts are priced in dollars. A rise in oil prices theoretically raises demand for dollars to pay for the oil. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 124.70 Japanese yen, up from 124.02. The dollar traded higher in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at 125.05 yen. By the time trading ended in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar fetched 125.33 yen, up from 124.08 yen late Monday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the British pound cost $ 1.8070 late Tuesday, cheaper for buyers than $ 1.8230 late Monday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the pound cost $ 1.7957, down from $ 1.8209 late Monday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> compared with rates late Monday: 1.7803 West German marks, up from 1.7645; 1.5035 Swiss francs, up from 1.4891; 1.2025 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1998; 6.0813 French francs, up from 6.0270; and 1,310.75 Italian lire, up from 1,300.75. Other late rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Monday: 1.7750 marks, up from 1.7625; 1.4995 Swiss francs, up from 1.4870; 6.0675 French francs, up from 6.0235; 2.0080 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9895; 1,309.32 Italian lire, up from 1,296.50; and 1.2000 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1995. In gold trading, bullion for current delivery fell 40 cents a troy ounce to $ 414 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, prices remained unchanged at $ 414.25. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> gold rose $ 1.25 to $ 413.50 and in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> it rose 5 cents to $ 415.67. Silver for current delivery fell 1.7 cents a troy ounce to $ 6.093 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> silver rose 3 cents an ounce to $ 6.11.
