<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Economy Bjt   12-20 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Economy, Bjt,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic, Market Factors Play Scrooge At Britain's Christmas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 High interest rates and slumping financial markets are casting Scrooge's shadow over Christmas for many British businesses and workers. Retailers say high interest rates _ the government's strategy for fighting inflation _ are depressing sales and prompting pre-holiday price markdowns. Industrial companies say their profits are feeling a pinch too, and investment firms have made major layoffs in the face of low trading volumes and fierce competition. The good news is that recent economic reports show the higher interest rates are beginning to slow the overheating economy. That means rates might not go higher. The bad news is that retailers are weathering a slowdown at what traditionally is one of the busiest times of the year. `` Trade is not what it usually is before Christmas. People are being more cautious with their money because of higher interest rates,'' said a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, whose 120 members operate stores on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s main shopping street. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> <PERSON> Mostaani </PERSON>, a 36-year-old secretary buying Christmas wrapping paper, said higher interest rates were affecting her shopping. `` We bought our first house in April, when the interest rate was 8 percent. I'm trying to buy less,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mostaani </PERSON> said. To slow spending, Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> pushed interest rates to 13 percent from June's decade-low 7.5 percent. Mortgage rates have risen to 12.75 percent from 11.5 percent and are expected to reach 13.5 percent in January. The annual inflation rate has picked up to 6.4 percent from 3.3 percent in January. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayliss </PERSON>, a 30-year-old accountant shopping in the same store as Mrs. <PERSON> Mostaani </PERSON>, also said he was worried about higher interest rates, but added: `` We'll not let it spoil Christmas, anyway.'' Some stores are taking pre-Christmas markdowns to move merchandise: <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a clothing and fabrics retailer, said it has reduced some women's designer clothes up to one-third. `` It's been a very difficult season for ladies fashions,'' said <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Dighton </PERSON>, a Liberty spokeswoman. But she added: `` We're experiencing a particularly good Christmas season. We expect -LRB- sales -RRB- to be up between 12 percent and 14 percent throughout the store.'' Meanwhile, investment firms in the <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s financial district, are laying off people because of competition and low trading volumes. The government's tight grip on spending also has hurt the market in gilts, or British government bonds. <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grenfell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> announced Dec. 6 it was shutting its gilt and equity market-making operations, cutting 450 jobs just before the holidays. It was the biggest single cutback announced since the October 1987 stock market crash and Big Bang, the 1986 deregulation of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s financial markets. Separately, the British textile group <ORGANIZATION> Coats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Viyella </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> warned Wednesday its pre-tax profit could fall as much as 40 percent in 1988, mostly because of high interest rates and the strong British pound. But some Britons have been encouraged by three economic reports released this past week which show the government's tactics appear to be working. The government reported last Friday that the annual inflation rate held steady at 6.4 percent in November. Last Thursday, it reported the underlying annual growth of average earnings fell to 9 percent in October from 9.25 percent in September. Earlier, it said retail sales fell 0.5 percent in November. `` The retail sales figures we saw at the beginning of the week were certainly helpful to show that demand is coming off a bit,'' said economist <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> of the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>. Economists now are expecting inflation to peak at between 7.25 percent and 7.5 percent next year rather than at 8 percent or higher, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said But he added: `` We wo n't really see evidence -LRB- of a slowdown -RRB- until the New Year.''
