<SECOND>AM-OECD-Inflation,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>OECD Says West Should Take Steps to Combat Inflation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Western industrialized nations are likely to experience moderately low inflation rates over the next two years, but the threat of accelerated inflation and higher interest rates is just over the horizon, the <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. In the latest issue of its semi-annual Economic Outlook, the secretariat of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> suggested that some tightening of fiscal policy, as well as monetary policy, may be necessary in most countries to combat inflationary pressures. The secretariat also predicted that the current-account trade deficits of the three biggest <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> countries _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> _ will remain unacceptably high The Paris-based <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> cautioned that although there appears to be no imminent problem, `` it would be unwise to conclude that external -LRB- trade -RRB- imbalances no longer represent an important threat to international financial stability.'' The report says the real, or inflation-adjusted, rate of expansion of western industrialized economies is likely to slow to between 2.5 percent and 3 percent in 1990 from 3.25 percent next year. The expansion rate this year was 4 percent. Growth in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is expected to slow to 2.5 percent in 1990 from 3 percent in 1989 and 3.75 percent this year. The <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> also suggested that the dollar may strengthen against other currencies in the short term, especially if the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy continues to expand at a rapid pace. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s growth rate is expected to moderate from a robust 5.75 percent in 1988 to 4.5 percent in 1989 and 3.75 percent in 1990. The outlook is similar in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where this year's growth rate of 3.75 percent is likely to decline to 2.5 percent in 1989, although there may be a very slight pickup to 2.75 percent in 1990. The organization's chief economist, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, described the overall picture for the <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> economies as `` rather encouraging.''
