<HEAD>Coffee Overflows Limit as Concerns Rise Over Dockworkers' Strike
in
Brazil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Coffee futures prices made their most dramatic surge in five consecutive sessions of advances, overrunning the daily trading limit Tuesday amid growing concerns over a lengthening strike by dockworkers in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. `` The longer the strike remains in place,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` the more explosive this will get.'' On other markets, cocoa moved in sympathy with coffee and registered sharp gains; platinum came off the floor and posted moderate gains after three straight days of reverses; and the January contract for crude oil futures skyrocketed $ 1.42 when the brokerage arm of a large commodity trading house got caught selling the market short on the day the contract expired. Coffee prices rocketed 10.35 cents and 10.58 cents for the spot March and May contracts, respectively, and settled up the 6-cent daily trading limit for the remaining deferred contracts at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION>, Sugar and <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. March closed at $ 1.5543 a pound, a high for the contract. <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> said the single-biggest development Tuesday was a report that a regional court near the key <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> port of <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> affirmed the legality of the strike that began Dec. 13. But several other factors were underpinning coffee's dramatic rise in recent days. `` There is concern about the production outlook ... insufficient rain in some parts of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> -LRB- the world's largest producer -RRB- and too much in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` And when you put those together, and then consider that the court decision leaves the workers under less pressure to settle quickly,'' he added, `` you've got the kind of explosive market we saw today.'' Cocoa, meanwhile, was up $ 58 to $ 82 a ton, with March at $ 1,524. `` It was the biggest day for cocoa in ages,'' said <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>. `` There was psychological spillover from the coffee pit and the port strike has some impact there too.'' `` And,'' he added, `` there is some indication the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> -LRB- the world's leading cocoa producer -RRB- is going to tighten supply by removing some from the market.'' Platinum climbed as high as $ 15 an ounce before settling $ 5 to $ 6.50 an ounce higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The December contract closed at $ 535.80 _ a steep decline from the $ 600 level the precious metal topped last week before <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced it had developed an automotive catalytic converter that did not require the use of platinum. `` People are coming back to platinum, but there are no bets how this will go until we get a complete story,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Chronowitz </PERSON>, vice president and director of futures research for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` How much will this actually cut demand? Will General Motors and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> follow suit? Those are questions we wo n't know answers to for a while,'' he added. `` But the worst may be over.'' The rest of the precious metals were quiet. Gold settled 40 cents to 50 cents lower at the <ORGANIZATION> Comex </ORGANIZATION>, with December at $ 414 a troy ounce; silver 1.7 cents to 2.1 cents lower, with December at $ 6.093 a troy ounce. Copper was .90 cent lower to 3.15 cents higher, with December at $ 1.5890 a pound. Crude oil futures at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rose only by 10 cents to 38 cents _ except for the spot contract in January, which jumped $ 1.42 to $ 17.73 a barrel jump, The spot-month aberration resulted because a brokerage firm, rumored to be part of grain giant <ORGANIZATION> Cargill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, had sold the market short _ expecting a drop in prices _ and was forced to buy contracts to fulfill obligations on delivery day. `` Somebody got caught between tornadoes,'' said energy analyst who declined to be identified, `` and had to buy like crazy. It seems to happen every time delivery day comes along.'' Heating oil settled 0.47 cent to 0.72 cent higher, with January at 51.47 cents a gallon, and unleaded gasoline was up 0.13 cent to 0.35 cent, with January at 45.55 cents a gallon. Grain and soybean futures prices posted across-the-board losses on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat settled -LCB- cent to 2 -LCB- cents lower, with December at $ 4.34 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 2 -LCB- cents to 3 -LCB- cents lower, with December at $ 2.67 a bushel; oats were 4 \ cents to 5 cents lower, with December at $ 2.21 a bushel; and soybeans were 3 -RCB- cents to 7 cents lower, with January at $ 7.86 -LCB- a bushel Livestock and pork futures prices were mixed at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </OR