<SECOND>BC-Texaco Settlement,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Unit To Pay $8.95 Million To Settle California Waste Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary has agreed to pay $ 8.95 million to settle a state complaint that it improperly stored hazardous wastes at its <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION> facility, state officials said Tuesday. Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> and state Health Director <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kizer </PERSON> called the settlement the largest ever reached under <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s hazardous waste law and possibly the biggest of its kind in the country. `` The severity of the penalties imposed in this case are matched by the seriousness of the violations and by the potential threat to public health and safety,'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said at a Capitol news conference. He said state investigators found about 5,000 steel drums containing hazardous waste at the <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> facility in northwest <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>. About 2,000 of the drums were leaking, corroded or open and more than 3,000 of them were not labeled, he said. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kizer </PERSON> said they had no indication that the waste had leaked into groundwater, but <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said the situation at the refinery could have been disasterous if there was a fire. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> spokesmen said the waste posed `` no significant risk to either our employees, the environment or the community.'' They said the company agreed to the settlement to avoid the costs of fighting the case in court. `` While technically hazardous waste, the vast majority of the materials were relatively inert and would not be considered to be hazardous outside <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>. `` Furthermore, procedures exist in the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> regulations under which <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> could have sought and, we are confident, obtained approvals from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> to treat most of the material involved as non-hazardous.'' <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bresnick </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, said most of the material stored in the drums already was there when <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> purchased property next to its facility from <ORGANIZATION> Tosco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. Most of the drums have been removed, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The company is required to remove the remaining drums within 90 days, state officials said. Under the settlement, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> will pay $ 4.5 million in civil penalties, $ 500,000 to cover administrative and investigative costs and at least $ 3.95 million to reduce waste production and improve waste handling procedures at its facilities. <PERSON> Kizer </PERSON> said the violations found by state inspectors included storing waste for longer than allowed without a permit, storing incompatible wastes next to each other, storing waste in unlabeled containers, and storing waste in open and unsafe conditions. According to the complaint, the department first found improper storage of waste at the site during a partial inspection in September 1986. The complaint was filed last week.
